{"title_page": "Jay Bradley", "text_new": "{{short description|American professional wrestler|bot=PearBOT 5}}\n{{about||the Mayo footballer|Aidan O'Shea (Mayo footballer)|the Kerry footballer|Aidan O'Shea (Kerry footballer)}}\n{{Infobox professional wrestler\n|name        = Jay Bradley\n|birthname   = Bradley Thomas Jay\n|image       = Jay Bradley Pro Wrestler.jpg\n|caption     = Bradley in February 2012\n|names       = '''Aiden O'Shea'''<ref>{{cite web|url=https://mobile.twitter.com/aidenosheatna|title=Aiden O'Shea official TNA Twitter}}</ref><br>Brad Bradley<ref name=\"OWOW\">{{cite web|url=http://www.onlineworldofwrestling.com/bios/j/jay-bradley/|title=Jay Bradley|accessdate=2013-06-23|publisher=Online World of Wrestling}}</ref><br />Bradley Jay<ref name=\"OWOW\"/><br />'''Jay Bradley'''<ref name=\"OWOW\"/><br />Ryan Braddock<ref name=\"OWOW\"/>\n|height      = {{height|ft=6|in=4}}<ref name=\"OWOW\"/><ref name=Wrestle1/>\n|weight      = {{convert|260|lb|kg|abbr=on}}<ref name=\"OWOW\"/>\n|birth_date  = {{Birth date and age|1980|11|17|mf=y}}<ref name=\"OWOW\"/>\n|birth_place = [[Downers Grove, Illinois]],<br>[[United States]]<ref name=\"OWOW\"/><ref name=Wrestle1/>\n|resides     = [[Chicago, Illinois]], [[United States]]\n|billed      = [[Chicago, Illinois]]<br>Southside of [[Chicago]]\n|trainer     = Steel Domain Wrestling<ref name=\"OWOW\"/><br />[[Ace Steel]]<ref name=\"OWOW\"/><br />Danny Dominion<ref name=\"OWOW\"/><br />Kevin Quinn<ref name=\"OWOW\"/><br />[[Deep South Wrestling]]<ref name=\"OWOW\"/>\n|debut       = 1999\n|retired     =\n}}\n'''Bradley Thomas Jay'''<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.facebook.com/bradjay?fref=hovercard|title=Bradley Thomas Facebook|date=2015-05-05|accessdate=2009-12-09|publisher=Facebook}}</ref> (born November 17, 1980) is an American [[Professional wrestling|professional wrestler]], best known for his time in [[Impact  Wrestling]]  under the [[ring name]]s of '''Jay Bradley''' and '''Aiden O'Shea'''. and [[WWE]]  as '''Ryan Braddock''' .\n\n==Professional wrestling career==\n===Early career (1999\u20132005)===\nBradley started his wrestling training at the Steel Domain Wrestling school in [[Chicago]], where he trained with wrestlers including [[CM Punk]] and [[Colt Cabana]]. Bradley suffered several setbacks in his career as he suffered from an [[Hyperthyroidism|overactive thyroid]].<ref name=\"punkcabana\">{{cite video|people=[[CM Punk]]; [[Colt Cabana]]|title=Straight Shootin' with CM Punk & Colt Cabana|medium=DVD|publisher=[[Ring of Honor]]|date=2005-07-01}}</ref> He worked for several [[Independent circuit|independent]] [[Professional wrestling promotion|promotions]] in the [[Mid-West]], most notably for [[Independent Wrestling Association Mid-South|IWA Mid-South]], before signing a developmental contract with [[World Wrestling Entertainment]] (WWE).\n\n===World Wrestling Entertainment===\n====Deep South Wrestling (2005\u20132007)====\nHe debuted in WWE's then-[[Farm team#Professional wrestling|developmental territory]] [[Deep South Wrestling]] (DSW) as \"The Monster of the Midway\" Bradley Jay. During his time in DSW he won the [[Deep South Heavyweight Championship]] on three occasions.<ref name=\"OWOW\"/> He also wrestled [[Glossary of professional wrestling terms#Dark match|dark matches]] for both the [[WWE Raw|Raw]] and [[WWE SmackDown|SmackDown!]] [[WWE Brand Extension|brands]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wrestlingcontent.com/2013/11/jay-bradley-will-soon-be-receiving.html|title=WWE Raw Results \u2013 February 26, 2007|date=2007-02-26|last=Watts|first=Barry|accessdate=2008-10-02|publisher=Online World of Wrestling}}</ref> Occasionally, he made appearances on ''[[WWE Heat|Heat]]'' as well.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.onlineworldofwrestling.com/results/raw/060403.html|title=WWE Raw Results \u2013 April 3, 2006|date=2006-04-03|accessdate=2008-10-02|publisher=Online World of Wrestling}}</ref> When WWE ended their relationship with DSW he was then sent to [[Ohio Valley Wrestling]] (OVW) to continue his development.<ref name=\"OWOW\"/>\n\n====Ohio Valley Wrestling (2007\u20132008)====\nOn May 16 he debuted in OVW under the name \"Jay Bradley\", defeating former [[OVW Heavyweight Championship|OVW Heavyweight Champion]], Chet the Jett.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.onlineworldofwrestling.com/results/ovw/_2007/|title=May 16, 2007 \u2013 OVW TV Tapings|date=2007-05-16|accessdate=2008-10-02|publisher=Online World Of Wrestling}}</ref> He defeated [[Paul Burchill]] and [[Damien Sandow|Idol Stevens]] in a three-way match via two Lariats to win the OVW Heavyweight Championship on June 1 at OVW's first ''Summer Sizzler Series'' event at [[Six Flags Kentucky Kingdom]] in [[Louisville, Kentucky]] to become the first man to hold both the OVW and DSW heavyweight titles.<ref name=\"OVW-heavyweight\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.onlineworldofwrestling.com/results/ovw/_2007/|title=June 1, 2007 \u2013 OVW Six Flags|date=2007-06-01|accessdate=2008-10-02|publisher=Online World Of Wrestling}}</ref> On June 15, 2007, at [[Ohio Valley Wrestling]]'s third ''Super Summer Sizzler Series'' event of the year at [[Six Flags Kentucky Kingdom]] in [[Louisville, Kentucky]], he defeated [[Damien Sandow|Idol Stevens]] to retain the OVW title.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.onlineworldofwrestling.com/results/ovw/_2007/|title=June 15, 2007 \u2013 OVW Six Flags| date=2007-06-15|accessdate=2008-10-02|publisher=Online World Of Wrestling}}</ref>\n\nHe then lost the title to Paul Burchill in a match taped on June 27 and aired on June 30. He also wrestled at Raw [[house show]]s on August 11 and 12 and September 1 (losing to \"Hacksaw\" [[Jim Duggan]]). He wrestled in a dark match against [[D'Lo Brown]] before a ''SmackDown'' television taping in August 2007.<ref name=\"OWOW\"/> On December 19, in OVW, he won the \"Love Thy Neighbor\" four corners tag team match to win a future OVW Heavyweight title shot.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.onlineworldofwrestling.com/results/ovw/_2007/|title=December 19, 2007 \u2013 OVW TV Tapings (Airs 12/29)|date=2007-10-19|accessdate=2008-10-02|publisher=Online World Of Wrestling}}</ref>\n\nHe then was starting a [[Feud (professional wrestling)|feud]] with [[Evan Bourne|Matt Sydal]] and had defeated him in a tag team match where he and Mike Kruel defeated Sydal and Charles Evans.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.onlineworldofwrestling.com/results/ovw/_2007/|title=January 23, 2008 \u2013 OVW TV Tapings|date=2008-01-23|accessdate=2008-10-02|publisher=Online World Of Wrestling}}</ref> Unfortunately, before Bradley could exercise his title opportunity, OVW was dropped by [[World Wrestling Entertainment]] as a development territory.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://corporate.wwe.com/news/2008/2008_02_07.jsp |title=WWE To Cease Affiliation With Ohio Valley Wrestling |date=2008-07-02 |accessdate=2008-10-17 |publisher=[[World Wrestling Entertainment]] |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080309213846/http://corporate.wwe.com/news/2008/2008_02_07.jsp |archivedate=2008-03-09 }}</ref>\n\n====''SmackDown!'' and Florida Championship Wrestling (2008\u20132009)====\nBradley debuted on the main ''SmackDown!'' roster on the August 15, 2008 episode of the show, under the name \"Ryan Braddock\".<ref name=\"SDdebut\"/> He was [[Squash (professional wrestling)|easily defeated]] by [[Big Show]] after a [[Hook (punch)|knockout punch]].<ref name=\"SDdebut\">{{cite web|url=http://www.wwe.com/shows/smackdown/archive/08152008/|title=A Gigantic debut|date=2008-08-15|last=Burdick|first=Michael|accessdate=2008-09-27|publisher=[[World Wrestling Entertainment]]}}</ref> At the August 14, 2008, [[Florida Championship Wrestling]] (FCW) television taping, Bradley wrestled under the Ryan Braddock name once again, making it his permanent and new [[ring name]]. On the August 22 episode of ''SmackDown!'', Braddock competed in a [[Battle royal (professional wrestling)|battle royal]] to qualify for the [[WWE Championship]] Scramble match at [[Unforgiven (2008)|Unforgiven]], but was eliminated by Big Show, who was not officially in the match.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wwe.com/shows/smackdown/archive/08222008/|title=Four chances at ultimate glory|date=2008-08-22|last=Burdick|first=Michael|accessdate=2008-10-02|publisher=[[World Wrestling Entertainment]]}}</ref> On the September 2 episode of ''[[ECW (WWE)|ECW]]'', Braddock faced [[Richard Young (wrestler)|Ricky Ortiz]] in a losing effort after being pinned by Ortiz's [[Professional wrestling attacks#Big splash|Big O]] finisher.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wwe.com/shows/ecw/archive/09022008/|title=Dirty Scrambles|date=2008-09-02|last=DiFino|first=Lennie|accessdate=2008-10-02|publisher=[[World Wrestling Entertainment]]}}</ref> On September 19 episode of ''SmackDown!'', Braddock competed in a one fall match-up with [[Drew Hankinson|Festus]], who was accompanied by [[Ray Gordy|Jesse]].<ref name=\"bubblewrap\">{{cite web|url=http://www.wwe.com/shows/smackdown/archive/09162008/|title= My Movers Co. is packing up SmackDown|date=2008-09-19|last=Burdick|first=Michael|accessdate=2008-10-02|publisher=[[World Wrestling Entertainment]]}}</ref> Braddock won the match as a result of a disqualification, after [[Jesse and Festus]] wrapped him in bubble wrap and duct tape.<ref name=\"bubblewrap\"/>\n\nFollowing this match, Braddock returned to FCW before being released from WWE in March 2009.<ref name=\"wwerelease\">{{cite web|url=http://www.wrestleview.com/viewnews.php?id=1236586051|title=WWE Smackdown wrestler released|date=2009-03-09|last=Martin|first=Adam|accessdate=2011-10-11|publisher=WrestleView}}</ref>\n\n===Independent circuit (2009\u2013present)===\nAfter his release from WWE, Bradley began working for the [[Berwyn, Illinois]] based [[All American Wrestling]] promotion and on March 28, 2009, defeated [[Seth Rollins|Tyler Black]], Chandler McClure and [[Egotistico Fantastico]] to win the [[AAW Heavyweight Championship]].<ref name=AAW>{{cite web|url=http://www.onlineworldofwrestling.com/results/aaw/|title=All American Wrestling results|accessdate=2010-08-22|work=Online World of Wrestling}}</ref> He held the title for five months, before losing it to [[Jimmy Jacobs]] on September 5.<ref name=AAW/> He also worked for Florida-based [[Full Impact Pro]], losing to [[T.J. Perkins]] in his debut match on June 6, 2009.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.fullimpactpro.com/index2.html|title=Hot Summer Nights 2009|accessdate=2010-08-22|publisher=[[Full Impact Pro]]|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100826032213/http://www.fullimpactpro.com/index2.html|archivedate=2010-08-26}}</ref>\n\nIn 2011, Bradley joined [[Billy Corgan]]'s wrestling promotion, [[Resistance Pro]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://resistancepro.com/talent/|title=Talent|accessdate=April 7, 2012|publisher=Resistance Pro}}</ref> At the promotion's debut show he defeated [[Icarus (wrestler)|Icarus]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://pwtorch.com/artman2/publish/radicanstake/article_56889.shtml|title=Radican's Resistance Pro DVD Review Series: \"Black Friday\" 11/25 \u2013 Steen vs. Smith, Briscoes vs. Akuma & Hart|date=January 13, 2012|last=Radican|first=Sean|accessdate=April 7, 2012|publisher=Pro Wrestling Torch}}</ref>\n\nIn November 2012, Bradley made his debut for [[Extreme Rising]] at their iPPV debut show Remember November defeating [[Christian York]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.wrestling-news.net/extreme-rising-results-remember/18636/ |title=Extreme Rising Results: Remember November \u2013 Monaca, PA (11/17) |publisher=Wrestling-News.net |accessdate=16 December 2012}}</ref>\n\nAt RPW Draw the Line, Bradley and Mad Man Pondo won the RPW Tag Team Championship.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.cagematch.net/?id=1&nr=116225 | title=RPW Draw the Line}}</ref> they were stripped of the titles on the same day.\n\nOn July 9, 2015, Bradley competed in a triple threat match against Joey Avalon and Matt Cage for [[Global Force Wrestling (2014\u20132017)|Global Force Wrestling]] for their GFW Grand Slam Tour in [[Appleton, Wisconsin]], Avalon won after pinning Cage.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cagematch.net/?id=1&nr=131276|title=GFW Grand Slam Tour - Appleton, WI results}}</ref>\n\n===Return to OVW (2013\u20132014)===\nBradley returned to [[Ohio Valley Wrestling|OVW]] after his appearance on [[TNA Gut Check|Impact Wrestling Gut Check]]. Bradley's first match since returning to OVW was against Tommy Gunn on March 6 which he won.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.cagematch.net/?id=2&nr=302&page=4 | title=Jay Bradley}}</ref> On May 8, Bradley teamed with [[Rob Terry]] to face The Coalition (Raul LaMotta & Shiloh Jonze) they ended up getting the victory by DQ after the other members of The Coalition interfered.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.cagematch.net/?id=1&nr=95528 | title=OVW TV #716}}</ref> On May 22, 2013, Bradley defeated the [[OVW Heavyweight Championship|OVW Heavyweight Champion]] [[Jamin Olivencia]] in a non-title match.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.cagematch.net/?id=1&nr=96143 | title=OVW TV #718}}</ref> On June 19, 2013, Bradley was defeated by Rob Terry in a number one contenders match for the OVW Heavyweight Championship.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cagematch.net/?id=1&nr=97087|title=OVW TV Tapings Results|date=2013-06-19|accessdate=2013-06-19|work=cagematch.net}}</ref> On September 7, 2013, Bradley unsuccessfully challenged Jamin Olivencia for the OVW Heavyweight Championship in a loaded boomstick on a pole match.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cagematch.net/?id=1&nr=100604|title=OVW Saturday Night Special 9/7/13 results}}</ref> On December 11, 2013, Bradley and Terry began teaming again getting wins over The Rockstars ([[Rockstar Spud]] and Ryan Howe) on two separate occasions.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cagematch.net/?id=1&nr=105200|title=OVW TV #748 results}}</ref> On January 1, 2014, Bradley defeated Deonta Davis and Leon Shelly in a two on one handicap match during an OVW Live Event.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cagematch.net/?id=1&nr=105681|title=OVW Live Event 1/1/14 results}}</ref> on January 4, 2014, Bradley faced Ryan Howe that ended in a no contest they had a rematch where Howe defeated Bradley in a street fight. on January 11, Bradley defeated Leon Shelly. on January 18, at OVW TV, Bradley defeated Bud Dwight. on January 25, Bradley defeated Robbie Walker. on February 1, 2014 at OVW TV, Bradley competed in the Nightmare rumble won by Johnny Spade. on February 1, 2014 at OVW Saturday Night Special, Bradley faced Ryan Howe in a losing effort.\n\n===Total Nonstop Action Wrestling (2013\u20132014)===\nOn the January 10, 2013 episode of ''[[Impact Wrestling (TV series)|Impact Wrestling]]'', Bradley appeared as part of the [[TNA Gut Check|Impact Wrestling Gut Check]], defeating [[Brian Cage]].<ref name=\"GutCheck\">{{cite web|url=http://www.wrestleview.com/viewnews.php?id=1357873493|title=Impact Results \u2013 01/10/13|date=January 10, 2013|last=Boutwell|first=Josh|accessdate=January 11, 2013|publisher=WrestleView}}</ref> The following week, Bradley was chosen over Cage by the storyline Gut Check judges to earn a contract in Impact Wrestling.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://pwtorch.com/artman2/publish/tnaimpact/article_67939.shtml|title= CALDWELL'S TNA IMPACT RESULTS 1/17: Complete coverage of the \"Why TNA May Want To Reconsider Being Live\" episode |last=Caldwell|first=James|date=2013-01-17|accessdate=2013-01-17|work=Pro Wrestling Torch}}</ref>\n\nBradley returned on the May 16 episode of ''Impact Wrestling'', defeating [[Christian York]] in the first qualifying round for the Bound for Glory Series Gut Check Tournament.<ref>{{cite web|title=CALDWELL'S TNA IMPACT RESULTS 5/16: Sting & Bully contract signing, X Title match, many Slammiversary developments|url=http://pwtorch.com/artman2/publish/tnaimpact/article_70633.shtml#.Ua0okkDVDCc}}</ref> On June 2 at [[Slammiversary XI]], Bradley defeated [[Samuel Shaw (wrestler)|Sam Shaw]] to qualify for the [[Bound for Glory Series#2013|2013 Bound for Glory Series]].<ref>{{cite web|title=CALDWELL'S TNA SLAMMIVERSARY PPV RESULTS (Hour 1): New X Division champion starts the show, Hogan has a potty-mouth, big TNA vs. Aces & Eights six-man tag match|url=http://pwtorch.com/artman2/publish/tnappvs/article_71024.shtml#.Ua0oFkDVDCc}}</ref> Bradley would go to lose all of his beginning matches in the BFG series to the likes of [[Austin Aries]], [[Hernandez (wrestler)|Hernandez]], and [[Abyss (wrestler)|Joseph Park]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://pwtorch.com/artman2/publish/tnaimpact/article_71423.shtml#.UdSPSflON6k|title=CALDWELL'S TNA IMPACT RESULTS 6/20: Complete \"virtual-time\" coverage of semi-live Impact - BFG Series kick-off, Open Fight Night, Sting takes out Aces & Eights, more}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=CALDWELL'S TNA IMPACT RESULTS 7/4: Sabin wins X Title & tears it up with Aries, BFG Series continues, more from Vegas|url=http://pwtorch.com/artman2/publish/tnaimpact/article_71730.shtml#.UemThY1OPz4}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=CALDWELL'S TNA IMPACT RESULTS 8/1: Complete \"virtual-time\" coverage of Aries vs. Styles, TNA Champ vs. X Champ, Mystery Reveal closes the show|url=http://pwtorch.com/artman2/publish/tnaimpact/article_72418.shtml#.Ufv4u5JOPz4}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=CALDWELL'S TNA IMPACT RESULTS 8/22: Complete \"virtual-time\" coverage of \"Hardcore Justice Night 2\" - Mafia vs. A&E loser leaves town, Old Styles, BFG Series, \"Brooke\" reintroduced|url=http://pwtorch.com/artman2/publish/tnaimpact/article_72883.shtml#.UhpqkhtOPz4}}</ref> Bradley ended his participation in the tournament on the August 28 episode of ''[[TNA Xplosion|Impact Wrestling Xplosion]]'', with a pinfall victory over Joseph Park, finishing eleventh out of the ten other wrestlers in a tie with Hernandez in the tournament.<ref>{{cite web|title=TNA NEWS: Updated BFG Series Standings following Impact|url=http://pwtorch.com/artman2/publish/TNA_News_1/article_71582.shtml#.UiD99xtOPz4}}</ref> On January 13, 2014, Bradley was released from his Impact Wrestling contract <ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.pwinsider.com/article/82826/another-tna-departure.html?p=1 | title=Another TNA Departure}}</ref>\n\n===Wrestle-1 (2013)===\nAs part of a working relationship between TNA and [[Wrestle-1]] it was announced on November 6, 2013, that Bradley would be working a tour for the [[Japan]]ese promotion between November 16 and December 1.<ref name=Wrestle1>{{cite web | url = http://www.w-1.co.jp/news/detail.php?id=2267 | title = 11.16\u5f8c\u697d\u5712\u5927\u4f1a\u3088\u308a\u53c2\u6226\u3059\u308b\u300cTNA\u63a8\u85a6\u9078\u624b\u300d\u6c7a\u5b9a\u306e\u304a\u77e5\u3089\u305b | date=2013-11-06 | accessdate=2013-11-08 | work=[[Wrestle-1]] | language=Japanese}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url = http://pwtorch.com/artman2/publish/TNA_News_1/article_74389.shtml | title = TNA news: Styles to defend TNA Title in Japan, two other TNA wrestlers to Japan for full tour | last=Caldwell | first=James | date=2013-11-06 | accessdate=2013-11-08 | work=Pro Wrestling Torch}}</ref> In their debut match for the promotion, Bradley and fellow TNA worker [[Rob Terry]] defeated [[Kaz Hayashi]] and [[Shuji Kondo]] in a tag team match.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.w-1.co.jp/schedule/tour.php?id=1437 | title=Wrestle-1 Tour 2013 | date=2013-11-16 | accessdate=2013-11-16 | work=[[Wrestle-1]] | language=Japanese | url-status=dead | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131019020045/http://www.w-1.co.jp/schedule/tour.php?id=1437 | archivedate=2013-10-19 }}</ref> Bradley and Terry remained undefeated in tag team matches for the entire tour, but Bradley's tour ended with a three match losing streak in singles matches against his fellow Impact Wrestling worker.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.w-1.co.jp/schedule/tour.php?id=1442 | title=Wrestle-1 Tour 2013 | date=2013-11-29 | accessdate=2013-12-01 | work=[[Wrestle-1]] | language=Japanese | url-status=dead | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131019020059/http://www.w-1.co.jp/schedule/tour.php?id=1442 | archivedate=2013-10-19 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.w-1.co.jp/schedule/tour.php?id=442 | title=The Ring \u30b3\u30e9\u30dc\u5927\u4f1a | date=2013-11-30 | accessdate=2013-12-01 | work=[[Wrestle-1]] | language=Japanese | url-status=dead | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131203003554/http://www.w-1.co.jp/schedule/tour.php?id=442 | archivedate=2013-12-03 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.w-1.co.jp/schedule/tour.php?id=440 | title=Wrestle-1 Tour 2013 | date=2013-12-01 | accessdate=2013-12-01 | work=[[Wrestle-1]] | language=Japanese | url-status=dead | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131203003111/http://www.w-1.co.jp/schedule/tour.php?id=440 | archivedate=2013-12-03 }}</ref>\n\n===Return to TNA (2015\u20132017)===\nOn October 4, 2015, at [[Bound for Glory (2015)|Bound for Glory]], Bradley made his return to [[Impact Wrestling]] under the ring name '''Aiden O'Shea''' (and began using an Irish [[ruffian (disambiguation)|ruffian]] gimmick) and competed in a twelve-man Bound For Gold Gauntlet match which was won by [[Brodus Clay|Tyrus]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wrestlezone.com/news/626597-tna-bound-for-glory-results-100415/2|title=TNA Bound For Glory Results (10/4) \u2013 New #1 Contender \u2018Bound For Gold\u2019, EY vs Angle, New World Champion!}}</ref> During October and November, O'Shea also competed in the first [[TNA World Title Series]] tournament that was taped in July 2015 as a member of Group Wildcard, where he ended third of his block by only defeating [[Crazzy Steve]] to receive 3 points. On January 8, 2016, at [[TNA One Night Only#One Night Only: Live|One Night Only: Live]], O'Shea was defeated by [[Rockstar Spud]] after they had a confrontation in the ring.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wrestlinginc.com/wi/news/2016/0108/606496/ongoing-tna-one-night-only-live-pay-per-view-results/|title=TNA 'One Night Only: Live!' PPV Results - Beer Money Reunites, Kurt Angle, Monster's Ball, More}}</ref> On the October 6, 2016 episode of ''Impact Wrestling'', O'Shea made his return to Impact Wrestling after his hiatus, accompanying Impact Wrestling President [[Billy Corgan]] to the ring and serving as muscle/representative. Bradley left TNA quietly in 2017.\n\n===Second Return to OVW (2017\u2013present)===\nO'Shea made his return to OVW on April 28, 2017 at Run For The Ropes III where he won a battle royal to face the [[OVW Heavyweight Championship]]. Later that night O'Shea was unsuccessful at winning the OVW Heavyweight Championship against Big Jon. On May 13, at OVW Saturday Night Special Uprising, Bradley was defeated by Justin Smooth. On June 2, 2018, Bradley and Shiloh Jonze unsuccessfully challenged The Bro Godz (Colton Cage & Dustin Jackson) for the OVW Southern Tag Team Championships. On August 23, Bradley was defeated by Jax Dane in the first round of the Grand Tournament.\nOn July 31, 2019, Bradley won a gauntlet match to become the new OVW Television Champion. Three days later, he and Cash Flo defeated Big Zo & Maximus Khan to become the new OVW Southern Tag Team Champions, thus making Bradley a double champion. On August 21, 2019, Bradley lose the OVW Television Championship to Maximus Khan in a Gauntlet match.\n\n===Pro Wrestling Noah (2018)===\nOn January 6, 2018, at the Korakuen Hall in Tokyo, Jay Bradley made his debut for [[Pro Wrestling Noah]] in a singles match against [[Takashi Sugiura]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://puroresuspirit.net/2017/12/noah-event-cards-for-january-february-2018|title=NOAH Event Cards for January & February 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Championships and accomplishments==\n*'''[[All American Wrestling]]'''\n**[[AAW Heavyweight Championship]] ([[AAW Heavyweight Championship#Title history|1 time]])<ref name=Wrestle1/><ref>{{cite web |url=http://aawrestling.com/titlehistory.html|title=AAW Heavyweight Title History |year=2007 |publisher=AAW Title Histories |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070303193736/http://www.aawrestling.com/titlehistory.html|archivedate=2007-03-03|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n*'''Pro Wrestling Blitz'''\n**PWB Heavyweight Championship (1 time, current)<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cagematch.net/?id=1&nr=168968|title=PWB Ring Wars results}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://mobile.twitter.com/AidenOsheaTNA/status/764663624996651009|title=#TheThug is your new BLITZwrestling Heavyweight Champion}}</ref>\n*'''[[Deep South Wrestling]]'''\n**[[Deep South Heavyweight Championship]] ([[Deep South Heavyweight Championship#Title history|3 times]])<ref name=\"OWOW\"/><ref name=Wrestle1/>\n*'''[[Independent Wrestling Association Mid-South]]'''\n**[[IWA Mid-South Tag Team Championship]] ([[IWA Mid-South Tag Team Championship#Title history|2 times]]) \u2013 with Ryan Boz (2) and Tirk Davis (1)<ref name=\"OWOW\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wrestling-titles.com/us/ky/iwams/iwams-t.html|title=IWA Mid-South Tag Team Championship history}}</ref>\n*'''Mid American Wrestling'''\n**MAW Heavyweight Championship (1 time)<ref name=\"MAW Heavyweight Title History\">{{cite web|url=http://www.cagematch.net/?id=5&nr=44|title=MAW Heavyweight Title History|accessdate=May 11, 2013|publisher=cagematch.net}}</ref>\n*'''[[Ohio Valley Wrestling]]'''\n**[[OVW Heavyweight Championship]] ([[OVW Heavyweight Championship#Title history|2 times]])<ref name=Wrestle1/><ref name=\"OVW-heavyweight\">{{cite web|url=http://www.ovwrestling.com/titles#heavyweight|title=OVW Heavyweight Championship|accessdate=April 7, 2012|publisher=[[Ohio Valley Wrestling]]|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110405184334/http://www.ovwrestling.com/titles#heavyweight|archivedate=April 5, 2011}}</ref>\n**[[OVW Television Championship]] ([[OVW Television Championship#Title history|1 time]])\n**[[OVW Southern Tag Team Championship]] ([[OVW Southern Tag Team Championship#Title history|2 times, current]]) \u2013 with Ca$h Flo, Big Zo and Hy-Zaya\n**[[Triple Crown (professional wrestling)#List of OVW Triple Crown Champions|Twenty-fifth OVW Triple Crown Champion]]\n*'''''[[Pro Wrestling Illustrated]]'''''\n**PWI ranked him #'''137''' of the top 500 singles wrestlers in the [[PWI 500]] in 2012<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.profightdb.com/pwi-500/2012.html | title = Pro Wrestling Illustrated (PWI) 500 for 2012 | accessdate=October 6, 2015 | work=The Internet Wrestling Database}}</ref>\n*'''[[Resistance Pro Wrestling]]'''\n**[[Resistance Pro Wrestling#RPW Tag Team Championship|RPW Tag Team Championship]] (1 time) \u2013 with [[Mad Man Pondo]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cagematch.net/?id=5&nr=1867|title=RPW Tag Team Championship history}}</ref>\n*'''Steel Domain Wrestling'''\n**SDW Heavyweight Championship (1 time)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.solie.org/titlehistories/htstdw.html|title=SDW STEEL DOMAIN WRESTLING WORLD HEAVYWEIGHT TITLE HISTORY|accessdate=2012-05-10|publisher=Solie.org}}</ref>\n*'''[[Impact Wrestling|Total Nonstop Action Wrestling]]'''\n**[[TNA Gut Check]] winner<ref name=\"TNA10January2013\">{{cite web|url=http://pwtorch.com/artman2/publish/tnaimpact/article_67774.shtml|title=Caldwell's TNA Impact Results 1/10: Complete \"virtual-time\" coverage of Sting-Knox, wedding angle, and, oh yeah, a PPV on Sunday (updated w/Box Score)|author=Caldwell, James|publisher=[[Pro Wrestling Torch Newsletter|PWTorch.com]]|date=January 10, 2013|accessdate=2013-01-11}}</ref>\n**[[Total Nonstop Action Wrestling tournaments#TNA Gut Check Tournament (2013)|TNA Gut Check Tournament (2013)]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cagematch.net/?id=26&nr=2818|title=TNA Gutcheck Tournament 2013 results}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20131203090339/http://www.w-1.co.jp//player/bradly.php Wrestle-1 profile]\n*{{twitter|JayBradleyPW|Jay Bradley}}\n*{{twitter|AidenOSheaTNA|Aiden O'Shea}}\n*{{facebook|jaybradleyimpactwrestling|Jay Bradley}}\n*{{IMDb name|id=3809498|name=Jay Bradley}}\n\n{{TNA Gut Check}}\n{{OVW Heavyweight Championship}}\n{{OVW Television Championship}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Bradley, Jay}}\n[[Category:1980 births]]\n[[Category:American male professional wrestlers]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from DeKalb, Illinois]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|American professional wrestler|bot=PearBOT 5}}\n{{for2|the Mayo footballer|[[Aidan O'Shea (Mayo footballer)]]|the Kerry footballer|[[Aidan O'Shea (Kerry footballer)]]}}\n{{Infobox professional wrestler\n|name        = Jay Bradley\n|birthname   = Bradley Thomas Jay\n|image       = Jay Bradley Pro Wrestler.jpg\n|caption     = Bradley in February 2012\n|names       = '''Aiden O'Shea'''<ref>{{cite web|url=https://mobile.twitter.com/aidenosheatna|title=Aiden O'Shea official TNA Twitter}}</ref><br>Brad Bradley<ref name=\"OWOW\">{{cite web|url=http://www.onlineworldofwrestling.com/bios/j/jay-bradley/|title=Jay Bradley|accessdate=2013-06-23|publisher=Online World of Wrestling}}</ref><br />Bradley Jay<ref name=\"OWOW\"/><br />'''Jay Bradley'''<ref name=\"OWOW\"/><br />Ryan Braddock<ref name=\"OWOW\"/>\n|height      = {{height|ft=6|in=4}}<ref name=\"OWOW\"/><ref name=Wrestle1/>\n|weight      = {{convert|260|lb|kg|abbr=on}}<ref name=\"OWOW\"/>\n|birth_date  = {{Birth date and age|1980|11|17|mf=y}}<ref name=\"OWOW\"/>\n|birth_place = [[Downers Grove, Illinois]],<br>[[United States]]<ref name=\"OWOW\"/><ref name=Wrestle1/>\n|resides     = [[Chicago, Illinois]], [[United States]]\n|billed      = [[Chicago, Illinois]]<br>Southside of [[Chicago]]\n|trainer     = Steel Domain Wrestling<ref name=\"OWOW\"/><br />[[Ace Steel]]<ref name=\"OWOW\"/><br />Danny Dominion<ref name=\"OWOW\"/><br />Kevin Quinn<ref name=\"OWOW\"/><br />[[Deep South Wrestling]]<ref name=\"OWOW\"/>\n|debut       = 1999\n|retired     =\n}}\n'''Bradley Thomas Jay'''<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.facebook.com/bradjay?fref=hovercard|title=Bradley Thomas Facebook|date=2015-05-05|accessdate=2009-12-09|publisher=Facebook}}</ref> (born November 17, 1980) is an American [[Professional wrestling|professional wrestler]], best known for his time in [[Impact  Wrestling]]  under the [[ring name]]s of '''Jay Bradley''' and '''Aiden O'Shea'''. and [[WWE]]  as '''Ryan Braddock''' .\n\n==Professional wrestling career==\n===Early career (1999\u20132005)===\nBradley started his wrestling training at the Steel Domain Wrestling school in [[Chicago]], where he trained with wrestlers including [[CM Punk]] and [[Colt Cabana]]. Bradley suffered several setbacks in his career as he suffered from an [[Hyperthyroidism|overactive thyroid]].<ref name=\"punkcabana\">{{cite video|people=[[CM Punk]]; [[Colt Cabana]]|title=Straight Shootin' with CM Punk & Colt Cabana|medium=DVD|publisher=[[Ring of Honor]]|date=2005-07-01}}</ref> He worked for several [[Independent circuit|independent]] [[Professional wrestling promotion|promotions]] in the [[Mid-West]], most notably for [[Independent Wrestling Association Mid-South|IWA Mid-South]], before signing a developmental contract with [[World Wrestling Entertainment]] (WWE).\n\n===World Wrestling Entertainment===\n====Deep South Wrestling (2005\u20132007)====\nHe debuted in WWE's then-[[Farm team#Professional wrestling|developmental territory]] [[Deep South Wrestling]] (DSW) as \"The Monster of the Midway\" Bradley Jay. During his time in DSW he won the [[Deep South Heavyweight Championship]] on three occasions.<ref name=\"OWOW\"/> He also wrestled [[Glossary of professional wrestling terms#Dark match|dark matches]] for both the [[WWE Raw|Raw]] and [[WWE SmackDown|SmackDown!]] [[WWE Brand Extension|brands]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wrestlingcontent.com/2013/11/jay-bradley-will-soon-be-receiving.html|title=WWE Raw Results \u2013 February 26, 2007|date=2007-02-26|last=Watts|first=Barry|accessdate=2008-10-02|publisher=Online World of Wrestling}}</ref> Occasionally, he made appearances on ''[[WWE Heat|Heat]]'' as well.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.onlineworldofwrestling.com/results/raw/060403.html|title=WWE Raw Results \u2013 April 3, 2006|date=2006-04-03|accessdate=2008-10-02|publisher=Online World of Wrestling}}</ref> When WWE ended their relationship with DSW he was then sent to [[Ohio Valley Wrestling]] (OVW) to continue his development.<ref name=\"OWOW\"/>\n\n====Ohio Valley Wrestling (2007\u20132008)====\nOn May 16 he debuted in OVW under the name \"Jay Bradley\", defeating former [[OVW Heavyweight Championship|OVW Heavyweight Champion]], Chet the Jett.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.onlineworldofwrestling.com/results/ovw/_2007/|title=May 16, 2007 \u2013 OVW TV Tapings|date=2007-05-16|accessdate=2008-10-02|publisher=Online World Of Wrestling}}</ref> He defeated [[Paul Burchill]] and [[Damien Sandow|Idol Stevens]] in a three-way match via two Lariats to win the OVW Heavyweight Championship on June 1 at OVW's first ''Summer Sizzler Series'' event at [[Six Flags Kentucky Kingdom]] in [[Louisville, Kentucky]] to become the first man to hold both the OVW and DSW heavyweight titles.<ref name=\"OVW-heavyweight\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.onlineworldofwrestling.com/results/ovw/_2007/|title=June 1, 2007 \u2013 OVW Six Flags|date=2007-06-01|accessdate=2008-10-02|publisher=Online World Of Wrestling}}</ref> On June 15, 2007, at [[Ohio Valley Wrestling]]'s third ''Super Summer Sizzler Series'' event of the year at [[Six Flags Kentucky Kingdom]] in [[Louisville, Kentucky]], he defeated [[Damien Sandow|Idol Stevens]] to retain the OVW title.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.onlineworldofwrestling.com/results/ovw/_2007/|title=June 15, 2007 \u2013 OVW Six Flags| date=2007-06-15|accessdate=2008-10-02|publisher=Online World Of Wrestling}}</ref>\n\nHe then lost the title to Paul Burchill in a match taped on June 27 and aired on June 30. He also wrestled at Raw [[house show]]s on August 11 and 12 and September 1 (losing to \"Hacksaw\" [[Jim Duggan]]). He wrestled in a dark match against [[D'Lo Brown]] before a ''SmackDown'' television taping in August 2007.<ref name=\"OWOW\"/> On December 19, in OVW, he won the \"Love Thy Neighbor\" four corners tag team match to win a future OVW Heavyweight title shot.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.onlineworldofwrestling.com/results/ovw/_2007/|title=December 19, 2007 \u2013 OVW TV Tapings (Airs 12/29)|date=2007-10-19|accessdate=2008-10-02|publisher=Online World Of Wrestling}}</ref>\n\nHe then was starting a [[Feud (professional wrestling)|feud]] with [[Evan Bourne|Matt Sydal]] and had defeated him in a tag team match where he and Mike Kruel defeated Sydal and Charles Evans.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.onlineworldofwrestling.com/results/ovw/_2007/|title=January 23, 2008 \u2013 OVW TV Tapings|date=2008-01-23|accessdate=2008-10-02|publisher=Online World Of Wrestling}}</ref> Unfortunately, before Bradley could exercise his title opportunity, OVW was dropped by [[World Wrestling Entertainment]] as a development territory.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://corporate.wwe.com/news/2008/2008_02_07.jsp |title=WWE To Cease Affiliation With Ohio Valley Wrestling |date=2008-07-02 |accessdate=2008-10-17 |publisher=[[World Wrestling Entertainment]] |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080309213846/http://corporate.wwe.com/news/2008/2008_02_07.jsp |archivedate=2008-03-09 }}</ref>\n\n====''SmackDown!'' and Florida Championship Wrestling (2008\u20132009)====\nBradley debuted on the main ''SmackDown!'' roster on the August 15, 2008 episode of the show, under the name \"Ryan Braddock\".<ref name=\"SDdebut\"/> He was [[Squash (professional wrestling)|easily defeated]] by [[Big Show]] after a [[Hook (punch)|knockout punch]].<ref name=\"SDdebut\">{{cite web|url=http://www.wwe.com/shows/smackdown/archive/08152008/|title=A Gigantic debut|date=2008-08-15|last=Burdick|first=Michael|accessdate=2008-09-27|publisher=[[World Wrestling Entertainment]]}}</ref> At the August 14, 2008, [[Florida Championship Wrestling]] (FCW) television taping, Bradley wrestled under the Ryan Braddock name once again, making it his permanent and new [[ring name]]. On the August 22 episode of ''SmackDown!'', Braddock competed in a [[Battle royal (professional wrestling)|battle royal]] to qualify for the [[WWE Championship]] Scramble match at [[Unforgiven (2008)|Unforgiven]], but was eliminated by Big Show, who was not officially in the match.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wwe.com/shows/smackdown/archive/08222008/|title=Four chances at ultimate glory|date=2008-08-22|last=Burdick|first=Michael|accessdate=2008-10-02|publisher=[[World Wrestling Entertainment]]}}</ref> On the September 2 episode of ''[[ECW (WWE)|ECW]]'', Braddock faced [[Richard Young (wrestler)|Ricky Ortiz]] in a losing effort after being pinned by Ortiz's [[Professional wrestling attacks#Big splash|Big O]] finisher.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wwe.com/shows/ecw/archive/09022008/|title=Dirty Scrambles|date=2008-09-02|last=DiFino|first=Lennie|accessdate=2008-10-02|publisher=[[World Wrestling Entertainment]]}}</ref> On September 19 episode of ''SmackDown!'', Braddock competed in a one fall match-up with [[Drew Hankinson|Festus]], who was accompanied by [[Ray Gordy|Jesse]].<ref name=\"bubblewrap\">{{cite web|url=http://www.wwe.com/shows/smackdown/archive/09162008/|title= My Movers Co. is packing up SmackDown|date=2008-09-19|last=Burdick|first=Michael|accessdate=2008-10-02|publisher=[[World Wrestling Entertainment]]}}</ref> Braddock won the match as a result of a disqualification, after [[Jesse and Festus]] wrapped him in bubble wrap and duct tape.<ref name=\"bubblewrap\"/>\n\nFollowing this match, Braddock returned to FCW before being released from WWE in March 2009.<ref name=\"wwerelease\">{{cite web|url=http://www.wrestleview.com/viewnews.php?id=1236586051|title=WWE Smackdown wrestler released|date=2009-03-09|last=Martin|first=Adam|accessdate=2011-10-11|publisher=WrestleView}}</ref>\n\n===Independent circuit (2009\u2013present)===\nAfter his release from WWE, Bradley began working for the [[Berwyn, Illinois]] based [[All American Wrestling]] promotion and on March 28, 2009, defeated [[Seth Rollins|Tyler Black]], Chandler McClure and [[Egotistico Fantastico]] to win the [[AAW Heavyweight Championship]].<ref name=AAW>{{cite web|url=http://www.onlineworldofwrestling.com/results/aaw/|title=All American Wrestling results|accessdate=2010-08-22|work=Online World of Wrestling}}</ref> He held the title for five months, before losing it to [[Jimmy Jacobs]] on September 5.<ref name=AAW/> He also worked for Florida-based [[Full Impact Pro]], losing to [[T.J. Perkins]] in his debut match on June 6, 2009.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.fullimpactpro.com/index2.html|title=Hot Summer Nights 2009|accessdate=2010-08-22|publisher=[[Full Impact Pro]]|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100826032213/http://www.fullimpactpro.com/index2.html|archivedate=2010-08-26}}</ref>\n\nIn 2011, Bradley joined [[Billy Corgan]]'s wrestling promotion, [[Resistance Pro]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://resistancepro.com/talent/|title=Talent|accessdate=April 7, 2012|publisher=Resistance Pro}}</ref> At the promotion's debut show he defeated [[Icarus (wrestler)|Icarus]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://pwtorch.com/artman2/publish/radicanstake/article_56889.shtml|title=Radican's Resistance Pro DVD Review Series: \"Black Friday\" 11/25 \u2013 Steen vs. Smith, Briscoes vs. Akuma & Hart|date=January 13, 2012|last=Radican|first=Sean|accessdate=April 7, 2012|publisher=Pro Wrestling Torch}}</ref>\n\nIn November 2012, Bradley made his debut for [[Extreme Rising]] at their iPPV debut show Remember November defeating [[Christian York]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.wrestling-news.net/extreme-rising-results-remember/18636/ |title=Extreme Rising Results: Remember November \u2013 Monaca, PA (11/17) |publisher=Wrestling-News.net |accessdate=16 December 2012}}</ref>\n\nAt RPW Draw the Line, Bradley and Mad Man Pondo won the RPW Tag Team Championship.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.cagematch.net/?id=1&nr=116225 | title=RPW Draw the Line}}</ref> they were stripped of the titles on the same day.\n\nOn July 9, 2015, Bradley competed in a triple threat match against Joey Avalon and Matt Cage for [[Global Force Wrestling (2014\u20132017)|Global Force Wrestling]] for their GFW Grand Slam Tour in [[Appleton, Wisconsin]], Avalon won after pinning Cage.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cagematch.net/?id=1&nr=131276|title=GFW Grand Slam Tour - Appleton, WI results}}</ref>\n\n===Return to OVW (2013\u20132014)===\nBradley returned to [[Ohio Valley Wrestling|OVW]] after his appearance on [[TNA Gut Check|Impact Wrestling Gut Check]]. Bradley's first match since returning to OVW was against Tommy Gunn on March 6 which he won.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.cagematch.net/?id=2&nr=302&page=4 | title=Jay Bradley}}</ref> On May 8, Bradley teamed with [[Rob Terry]] to face The Coalition (Raul LaMotta & Shiloh Jonze) they ended up getting the victory by DQ after the other members of The Coalition interfered.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.cagematch.net/?id=1&nr=95528 | title=OVW TV #716}}</ref> On May 22, 2013, Bradley defeated the [[OVW Heavyweight Championship|OVW Heavyweight Champion]] [[Jamin Olivencia]] in a non-title match.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.cagematch.net/?id=1&nr=96143 | title=OVW TV #718}}</ref> On June 19, 2013, Bradley was defeated by Rob Terry in a number one contenders match for the OVW Heavyweight Championship.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cagematch.net/?id=1&nr=97087|title=OVW TV Tapings Results|date=2013-06-19|accessdate=2013-06-19|work=cagematch.net}}</ref> On September 7, 2013, Bradley unsuccessfully challenged Jamin Olivencia for the OVW Heavyweight Championship in a loaded boomstick on a pole match.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cagematch.net/?id=1&nr=100604|title=OVW Saturday Night Special 9/7/13 results}}</ref> On December 11, 2013, Bradley and Terry began teaming again getting wins over The Rockstars ([[Rockstar Spud]] and Ryan Howe) on two separate occasions.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cagematch.net/?id=1&nr=105200|title=OVW TV #748 results}}</ref> On January 1, 2014, Bradley defeated Deonta Davis and Leon Shelly in a two on one handicap match during an OVW Live Event.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cagematch.net/?id=1&nr=105681|title=OVW Live Event 1/1/14 results}}</ref> on January 4, 2014, Bradley faced Ryan Howe that ended in a no contest they had a rematch where Howe defeated Bradley in a street fight. on January 11, Bradley defeated Leon Shelly. on January 18, at OVW TV, Bradley defeated Bud Dwight. on January 25, Bradley defeated Robbie Walker. on February 1, 2014 at OVW TV, Bradley competed in the Nightmare rumble won by Johnny Spade. on February 1, 2014 at OVW Saturday Night Special, Bradley faced Ryan Howe in a losing effort.\n\n===Total Nonstop Action Wrestling (2013\u20132014)===\nOn the January 10, 2013 episode of ''[[Impact Wrestling (TV series)|Impact Wrestling]]'', Bradley appeared as part of the [[TNA Gut Check|Impact Wrestling Gut Check]], defeating [[Brian Cage]].<ref name=\"GutCheck\">{{cite web|url=http://www.wrestleview.com/viewnews.php?id=1357873493|title=Impact Results \u2013 01/10/13|date=January 10, 2013|last=Boutwell|first=Josh|accessdate=January 11, 2013|publisher=WrestleView}}</ref> The following week, Bradley was chosen over Cage by the storyline Gut Check judges to earn a contract in Impact Wrestling.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://pwtorch.com/artman2/publish/tnaimpact/article_67939.shtml|title= CALDWELL'S TNA IMPACT RESULTS 1/17: Complete coverage of the \"Why TNA May Want To Reconsider Being Live\" episode |last=Caldwell|first=James|date=2013-01-17|accessdate=2013-01-17|work=Pro Wrestling Torch}}</ref>\n\nBradley returned on the May 16 episode of ''Impact Wrestling'', defeating [[Christian York]] in the first qualifying round for the Bound for Glory Series Gut Check Tournament.<ref>{{cite web|title=CALDWELL'S TNA IMPACT RESULTS 5/16: Sting & Bully contract signing, X Title match, many Slammiversary developments|url=http://pwtorch.com/artman2/publish/tnaimpact/article_70633.shtml#.Ua0okkDVDCc}}</ref> On June 2 at [[Slammiversary XI]], Bradley defeated [[Samuel Shaw (wrestler)|Sam Shaw]] to qualify for the [[Bound for Glory Series#2013|2013 Bound for Glory Series]].<ref>{{cite web|title=CALDWELL'S TNA SLAMMIVERSARY PPV RESULTS (Hour 1): New X Division champion starts the show, Hogan has a potty-mouth, big TNA vs. Aces & Eights six-man tag match|url=http://pwtorch.com/artman2/publish/tnappvs/article_71024.shtml#.Ua0oFkDVDCc}}</ref> Bradley would go to lose all of his beginning matches in the BFG series to the likes of [[Austin Aries]], [[Hernandez (wrestler)|Hernandez]], and [[Abyss (wrestler)|Joseph Park]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://pwtorch.com/artman2/publish/tnaimpact/article_71423.shtml#.UdSPSflON6k|title=CALDWELL'S TNA IMPACT RESULTS 6/20: Complete \"virtual-time\" coverage of semi-live Impact - BFG Series kick-off, Open Fight Night, Sting takes out Aces & Eights, more}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=CALDWELL'S TNA IMPACT RESULTS 7/4: Sabin wins X Title & tears it up with Aries, BFG Series continues, more from Vegas|url=http://pwtorch.com/artman2/publish/tnaimpact/article_71730.shtml#.UemThY1OPz4}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=CALDWELL'S TNA IMPACT RESULTS 8/1: Complete \"virtual-time\" coverage of Aries vs. Styles, TNA Champ vs. X Champ, Mystery Reveal closes the show|url=http://pwtorch.com/artman2/publish/tnaimpact/article_72418.shtml#.Ufv4u5JOPz4}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=CALDWELL'S TNA IMPACT RESULTS 8/22: Complete \"virtual-time\" coverage of \"Hardcore Justice Night 2\" - Mafia vs. A&E loser leaves town, Old Styles, BFG Series, \"Brooke\" reintroduced|url=http://pwtorch.com/artman2/publish/tnaimpact/article_72883.shtml#.UhpqkhtOPz4}}</ref> Bradley ended his participation in the tournament on the August 28 episode of ''[[TNA Xplosion|Impact Wrestling Xplosion]]'', with a pinfall victory over Joseph Park, finishing eleventh out of the ten other wrestlers in a tie with Hernandez in the tournament.<ref>{{cite web|title=TNA NEWS: Updated BFG Series Standings following Impact|url=http://pwtorch.com/artman2/publish/TNA_News_1/article_71582.shtml#.UiD99xtOPz4}}</ref> On January 13, 2014, Bradley was released from his Impact Wrestling contract <ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.pwinsider.com/article/82826/another-tna-departure.html?p=1 | title=Another TNA Departure}}</ref>\n\n===Wrestle-1 (2013)===\nAs part of a working relationship between TNA and [[Wrestle-1]] it was announced on November 6, 2013, that Bradley would be working a tour for the [[Japan]]ese promotion between November 16 and December 1.<ref name=Wrestle1>{{cite web | url = http://www.w-1.co.jp/news/detail.php?id=2267 | title = 11.16\u5f8c\u697d\u5712\u5927\u4f1a\u3088\u308a\u53c2\u6226\u3059\u308b\u300cTNA\u63a8\u85a6\u9078\u624b\u300d\u6c7a\u5b9a\u306e\u304a\u77e5\u3089\u305b | date=2013-11-06 | accessdate=2013-11-08 | work=[[Wrestle-1]] | language=Japanese}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url = http://pwtorch.com/artman2/publish/TNA_News_1/article_74389.shtml | title = TNA news: Styles to defend TNA Title in Japan, two other TNA wrestlers to Japan for full tour | last=Caldwell | first=James | date=2013-11-06 | accessdate=2013-11-08 | work=Pro Wrestling Torch}}</ref> In their debut match for the promotion, Bradley and fellow TNA worker [[Rob Terry]] defeated [[Kaz Hayashi]] and [[Shuji Kondo]] in a tag team match.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.w-1.co.jp/schedule/tour.php?id=1437 | title=Wrestle-1 Tour 2013 | date=2013-11-16 | accessdate=2013-11-16 | work=[[Wrestle-1]] | language=Japanese | url-status=dead | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131019020045/http://www.w-1.co.jp/schedule/tour.php?id=1437 | archivedate=2013-10-19 }}</ref> Bradley and Terry remained undefeated in tag team matches for the entire tour, but Bradley's tour ended with a three match losing streak in singles matches against his fellow Impact Wrestling worker.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.w-1.co.jp/schedule/tour.php?id=1442 | title=Wrestle-1 Tour 2013 | date=2013-11-29 | accessdate=2013-12-01 | work=[[Wrestle-1]] | language=Japanese | url-status=dead | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131019020059/http://www.w-1.co.jp/schedule/tour.php?id=1442 | archivedate=2013-10-19 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.w-1.co.jp/schedule/tour.php?id=442 | title=The Ring \u30b3\u30e9\u30dc\u5927\u4f1a | date=2013-11-30 | accessdate=2013-12-01 | work=[[Wrestle-1]] | language=Japanese | url-status=dead | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131203003554/http://www.w-1.co.jp/schedule/tour.php?id=442 | archivedate=2013-12-03 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.w-1.co.jp/schedule/tour.php?id=440 | title=Wrestle-1 Tour 2013 | date=2013-12-01 | accessdate=2013-12-01 | work=[[Wrestle-1]] | language=Japanese | url-status=dead | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131203003111/http://www.w-1.co.jp/schedule/tour.php?id=440 | archivedate=2013-12-03 }}</ref>\n\n===Return to TNA (2015\u20132017)===\nOn October 4, 2015, at [[Bound for Glory (2015)|Bound for Glory]], Bradley made his return to [[Impact Wrestling]] under the ring name '''Aiden O'Shea''' (and began using an Irish [[ruffian (disambiguation)|ruffian]] gimmick) and competed in a twelve-man Bound For Gold Gauntlet match which was won by [[Brodus Clay|Tyrus]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wrestlezone.com/news/626597-tna-bound-for-glory-results-100415/2|title=TNA Bound For Glory Results (10/4) \u2013 New #1 Contender \u2018Bound For Gold\u2019, EY vs Angle, New World Champion!}}</ref> During October and November, O'Shea also competed in the first [[TNA World Title Series]] tournament that was taped in July 2015 as a member of Group Wildcard, where he ended third of his block by only defeating [[Crazzy Steve]] to receive 3 points. On January 8, 2016, at [[TNA One Night Only#One Night Only: Live|One Night Only: Live]], O'Shea was defeated by [[Rockstar Spud]] after they had a confrontation in the ring.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wrestlinginc.com/wi/news/2016/0108/606496/ongoing-tna-one-night-only-live-pay-per-view-results/|title=TNA 'One Night Only: Live!' PPV Results - Beer Money Reunites, Kurt Angle, Monster's Ball, More}}</ref> On the October 6, 2016 episode of ''Impact Wrestling'', O'Shea made his return to Impact Wrestling after his hiatus, accompanying Impact Wrestling President [[Billy Corgan]] to the ring and serving as muscle/representative. Bradley left TNA quietly in 2017.\n\n===Second Return to OVW (2017\u2013present)===\nO'Shea made his return to OVW on April 28, 2017 at Run For The Ropes III where he won a battle royal to face the [[OVW Heavyweight Championship]]. Later that night O'Shea was unsuccessful at winning the OVW Heavyweight Championship against Big Jon. On May 13, at OVW Saturday Night Special Uprising, Bradley was defeated by Justin Smooth. On June 2, 2018, Bradley and Shiloh Jonze unsuccessfully challenged The Bro Godz (Colton Cage & Dustin Jackson) for the OVW Southern Tag Team Championships. On August 23, Bradley was defeated by Jax Dane in the first round of the Grand Tournament.\nOn July 31, 2019, Bradley won a gauntlet match to become the new OVW Television Champion. Three days later, he and Cash Flo defeated Big Zo & Maximus Khan to become the new OVW Southern Tag Team Champions, thus making Bradley a double champion. On August 21, 2019, Bradley lose the OVW Television Championship to Maximus Khan in a Gauntlet match.\n\n===Pro Wrestling Noah (2018)===\nOn January 6, 2018, at the Korakuen Hall in Tokyo, Jay Bradley made his debut for [[Pro Wrestling Noah]] in a singles match against [[Takashi Sugiura]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://puroresuspirit.net/2017/12/noah-event-cards-for-january-february-2018|title=NOAH Event Cards for January & February 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Championships and accomplishments==\n*'''[[All American Wrestling]]'''\n**[[AAW Heavyweight Championship]] ([[AAW Heavyweight Championship#Title history|1 time]])<ref name=Wrestle1/><ref>{{cite web |url=http://aawrestling.com/titlehistory.html|title=AAW Heavyweight Title History |year=2007 |publisher=AAW Title Histories |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070303193736/http://www.aawrestling.com/titlehistory.html|archivedate=2007-03-03|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n*'''Pro Wrestling Blitz'''\n**PWB Heavyweight Championship (1 time, current)<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cagematch.net/?id=1&nr=168968|title=PWB Ring Wars results}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://mobile.twitter.com/AidenOsheaTNA/status/764663624996651009|title=#TheThug is your new BLITZwrestling Heavyweight Champion}}</ref>\n*'''[[Deep South Wrestling]]'''\n**[[Deep South Heavyweight Championship]] ([[Deep South Heavyweight Championship#Title history|3 times]])<ref name=\"OWOW\"/><ref name=Wrestle1/>\n*'''[[Independent Wrestling Association Mid-South]]'''\n**[[IWA Mid-South Tag Team Championship]] ([[IWA Mid-South Tag Team Championship#Title history|2 times]]) \u2013 with Ryan Boz (2) and Tirk Davis (1)<ref name=\"OWOW\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wrestling-titles.com/us/ky/iwams/iwams-t.html|title=IWA Mid-South Tag Team Championship history}}</ref>\n*'''Mid American Wrestling'''\n**MAW Heavyweight Championship (1 time)<ref name=\"MAW Heavyweight Title History\">{{cite web|url=http://www.cagematch.net/?id=5&nr=44|title=MAW Heavyweight Title History|accessdate=May 11, 2013|publisher=cagematch.net}}</ref>\n*'''[[Ohio Valley Wrestling]]'''\n**[[OVW Heavyweight Championship]] ([[OVW Heavyweight Championship#Title history|2 times]])<ref name=Wrestle1/><ref name=\"OVW-heavyweight\">{{cite web|url=http://www.ovwrestling.com/titles#heavyweight|title=OVW Heavyweight Championship|accessdate=April 7, 2012|publisher=[[Ohio Valley Wrestling]]|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110405184334/http://www.ovwrestling.com/titles#heavyweight|archivedate=April 5, 2011}}</ref>\n**[[OVW Television Championship]] ([[OVW Television Championship#Title history|1 time]])\n**[[OVW Southern Tag Team Championship]] ([[OVW Southern Tag Team Championship#Title history|2 times, current]]) \u2013 with Ca$h Flo, Big Zo and Hy-Zaya\n**[[Triple Crown (professional wrestling)#List of OVW Triple Crown Champions|Twenty-fifth OVW Triple Crown Champion]]\n*'''''[[Pro Wrestling Illustrated]]'''''\n**PWI ranked him #'''137''' of the top 500 singles wrestlers in the [[PWI 500]] in 2012<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.profightdb.com/pwi-500/2012.html | title = Pro Wrestling Illustrated (PWI) 500 for 2012 | accessdate=October 6, 2015 | work=The Internet Wrestling Database}}</ref>\n*'''[[Resistance Pro Wrestling]]'''\n**[[Resistance Pro Wrestling#RPW Tag Team Championship|RPW Tag Team Championship]] (1 time) \u2013 with [[Mad Man Pondo]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cagematch.net/?id=5&nr=1867|title=RPW Tag Team Championship history}}</ref>\n*'''Steel Domain Wrestling'''\n**SDW Heavyweight Championship (1 time)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.solie.org/titlehistories/htstdw.html|title=SDW STEEL DOMAIN WRESTLING WORLD HEAVYWEIGHT TITLE HISTORY|accessdate=2012-05-10|publisher=Solie.org}}</ref>\n*'''[[Impact Wrestling|Total Nonstop Action Wrestling]]'''\n**[[TNA Gut Check]] winner<ref name=\"TNA10January2013\">{{cite web|url=http://pwtorch.com/artman2/publish/tnaimpact/article_67774.shtml|title=Caldwell's TNA Impact Results 1/10: Complete \"virtual-time\" coverage of Sting-Knox, wedding angle, and, oh yeah, a PPV on Sunday (updated w/Box Score)|author=Caldwell, James|publisher=[[Pro Wrestling Torch Newsletter|PWTorch.com]]|date=January 10, 2013|accessdate=2013-01-11}}</ref>\n**[[Total Nonstop Action Wrestling tournaments#TNA Gut Check Tournament (2013)|TNA Gut Check Tournament (2013)]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cagematch.net/?id=26&nr=2818|title=TNA Gutcheck Tournament 2013 results}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20131203090339/http://www.w-1.co.jp//player/bradly.php Wrestle-1 profile]\n*{{twitter|JayBradleyPW|Jay Bradley}}\n*{{twitter|AidenOSheaTNA|Aiden O'Shea}}\n*{{facebook|jaybradleyimpactwrestling|Jay Bradley}}\n*{{IMDb name|id=3809498|name=Jay Bradley}}\n\n{{TNA Gut Check}}\n{{OVW Heavyweight Championship}}\n{{OVW Television Championship}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Bradley, Jay}}\n[[Category:1980 births]]\n[[Category:American male professional wrestlers]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from DeKalb, Illinois]]\n", "name_user": "Nihiltres", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200etop:Simplified hatnote syntax", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Jay_Bradley"}
{"title_page": "Steve Reed (politician)", "text_new": "{{other people||Steve Reed (disambiguation)}}\n{{Short description|British politician and Member of Parliament  for Croydon North}}\n{{EngvarB|date=May 2015}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=June 2017}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| honorific-prefix = \n| name = Steve Reed\n| honorific-suffix = [[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|MP]] [[OBE]]\n| image = Official portrait of Mr Steve Reed crop 2.jpg\n| office = [[Shadow Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government]]\n| leader = [[Sir Keir Starmer]]\n| predecessor = [[Andrew Gwynne]]\n| successor = \n| term_start = 6 April 2020\n| term_end =\n| office1 = [[Department for Education|Shadow Minister for Children and Families]]\n| leader1 = [[Jeremy Corbyn]]\n| term_start1 = 24 June 2019\n| term_end1 = 6 April 2020\n| predecessor1 = [[Emma Lewell-Buck]]\n| successor1 = [[Tulip Siddiq]]\n| office2  = [[Department for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport|Shadow Minister for Civil Society]]\n| leader2  = [[Jeremy Corbyn]]\n| term_start2 = 3 October 2016\n| term_end2  = 24 June 2019\n| predecessor2 = [[Ian Lavery]]\n| successor2 = [[Vicky Foxcroft]]\n| office3 = [[Ministry of Housing, Communities and Local Government|Shadow Minister for Local Government]]\n| leader3 = [[Harriet Harman]] <small>''(Acting)''</small> <br> [[Jeremy Corbyn]]\n| term_start3 = 8 May 2015\n| term_end3  = 27 June 2016\n| predecessor3 = [[Andy Sawford]]\n| successor3  = [[Jim McMahon]]\n| office4  = [[Home Office|Shadow Home Office Minister]]\n| leader4  = [[Ed Miliband]]\n| term_start4 = 7 October 2013\n| term_end4   = 8 May 2015\n| predecessor4 = [[Gloria de Piero]]\n| successor4 = [[Lyn Brown]]\n| office5 = [[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|Member of Parliament]] <br /> for [[Croydon North (UK Parliament constituency)|Croydon North]]\n| term_start5 = 29 November 2012\n| term_end5 = \n| majority5 = 24,673 (44.3%)<ref name=\"bbc-2015-election\">{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/politics/constituencies/E14000655|title=Croydon North parliamentary constituency \u2013 Election 2015|publisher=BBC News|date=8 May 2015|accessdate=11 May 2015}}</ref>\n| predecessor5 = [[Malcolm Wicks]]\n| successor5 = \n| office6 = [[Lambeth London Borough Council|Leader of Lambeth Council]]\n| deputy6 = Jackie Meldrum\n| term_start6 = 4 May 2006\n| term_end6 = 29 November 2012\n| predecessor6 = Peter Truesdale\n| successor6 = Lib Peck\n| birth_name = Steven Mark Ward Reed\n| birth_date = {{Birth date and age|df=yes|1963|11|12}}\n| birth_place = [[St Albans]], [[Hertfordshire]], England\n| death_date = \n| death_place = \n| nationality = British\n| spouse = \n| party = [[Labour and Co-operative]]\n| relations = \n| children = \n| residence = \n| alma_mater = [[University of Sheffield]]\n| occupation = \n| profession = \n| signature = \n| website = [http://www.stevereedmp.co.uk SteveReedMP.co.uk]\n| footnotes = \n}}\n\n'''Steven Mark Ward Reed''' {{Post-nominals|country=GBR|size=100%|OBE}} (born 12 November 1963) is a British [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour]] and [[Co-operative Party]] politician who has been the [[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|Member of Parliament]] (MP) for [[Croydon North (UK Parliament constituency)|Croydon North]] since [[2012 Croydon North by-election|2012]]. He was previously the [[Lambeth Council|Leader of Lambeth Council]] from 2006 to 2012.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.lambeth.gov.uk/moderngov/mgUserInfo.aspx?UID%3D134|title=Committee details - Councillor Steve Reed|access-date=20 June 2010 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100516064339/http://www.lambeth.gov.uk/moderngov/mgUserInfo.aspx?UID=134 |archive-date=16 May 2010 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://labourlist.org/2012/11/steve-reed-selected-as-labours-candidate-in-croydon-north/ |title=Steve Reed selected as Labour's candidate in Croydon North |publisher=LabourList |date=3 November 2012 |accessdate=10 June 2017}}</ref> Reed does not hold responsibilities for [[Housing in England]], as [[Thangam Debbonaire]] serves as [[Shadow Secretary of State for Housing]], as if Labour form the next government, they will create a separate [[government department]] for housing.\n\n==Early life==\nReed was born and raised in [[St Albans]], [[Hertfordshire]], and his family worked at [[Odhams]] printing factory in [[Watford]] until it closed down in 1983.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.freebmd.org.uk/cgi/information.pl?cite=TpITzPC61DGIG7OxE0mkvg&scan=1|title=Reed Steven MW|accessdate=26 February 2018|work=FreeBMD|publisher=ONS}}</ref><ref name=\"CroydonNorth\">{{cite news|author=Gareth Davies |url=http://www.thisiscroydontoday.co.uk/Steve-Reed-favourite-Croydon-North-Lambeth/story-17426335-detail/story.html |title=Steve Reed: A favourite in Croydon North but not in Lambeth?|work=Croydon Advertiser |publisher=Local World|via=This is Croydon Today|date=26 November 2012 |accessdate=10 June 2017}}{{deadlink|date=January 2020}}</ref> Around this time, he joined the Labour Party before going on to study English at [[Sheffield University]].<ref name=\"CroydonNorth\" /> He worked in the educational publishing industry from 1990 to 2008.<ref name=\"CroydonNorth\" />\n\nIn March 2008 he narrowly lost out to [[Chuka Umunna]] for selection as Labour's 2010 election candidate for the [[Streatham (UK Parliament constituency)|Streatham constituency]].\n\n==Lambeth Council==\nReed first stood for the [[Lambeth London Borough Council]] in the [[1998 Lambeth Council election|1998 election]] and won the Town Hall ward (now [[Brixton Hill]]). In [[2002 Lambeth Council election|2002]] Labour lost control of Lambeth council to a Conservative/Liberal Democrat coalition, and in response, Reed was elected leader of the opposition.\n\nAfter Labour won back control of [[Lambeth Council]] in [[2006 Lambeth Council election|2006]], Reed was appointed the council's leader. During his tenure, Lambeth went from being rated London's worst-run borough, with a one-star rating in the [[Audit Commission (United Kingdom)|Audit Commission]]'s annual inspection in 2006, to having a three-star rating in 2009.<ref>{{cite news|publisher=ESI Media|url=https://www.standard.co.uk/news/lambeth-is-londons-worstrun-borough-7213025.html|title=Lambeth is London's worst-run borough|author=Ross Lydall|work=Evening Standard|date=22 February 2007}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://cpa.audit-commission.gov.uk/STCCScorecard.aspx?taxid=104598 |title=London Borough of Lambeth Comprehensive Performance Assessment (CPA) scorecard 2008|access-date=20 June 2010|url-status=dead |archive-url=http://webarchive.nationalarchives.gov.uk/20090414003855/http%3A//cpa.audit%2Dcommission.gov.uk/STCCScorecard.aspx?TaxID%3D104598 |archive-date=14 April 2009 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> At the [[2010 Lambeth Council election|2010 election]], Labour gained seats from the [[Liberal Democrats (UK)|Liberal Democrats]] and [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservatives]], making it the first time that Labour had been re-elected to lead in Lambeth for twenty years.\n\nReed held a number of significant positions in local government. He was:\n\n* Deputy Leader of Local Government Labour, an association representing Labour councillors nationally;<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.labourgroup.lga.gov.uk/lga/core/page.do?pageId=1828919|title=Labour Group Officers |access-date=14 January 2020|url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101012114836/http://www.labourgroup.lga.gov.uk/lga/core/page.do?pageId=1828919 |archive-date=12 October 2010 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n* Deputy Chairman of the Local Government Association;<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.lga.gov.uk/lga/councillor/profile-display.do?id=1716688|title=Cllr Steve Reed - Deputy Chair, LGA|publisher=Local Government Association|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110928072239/http://www.lga.gov.uk/lga/councillor/profile-display.do?id=1716688|archive-date=28 September 2011|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n* London Councils board member for Children's Services and Employment;<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.londoncouncils.gov.uk/aboutus/organisation/leadingmembers/stevereed.htm |title=Cllr Steve Reed - Executive member for children's services and skills and employment (Labour) |access-date=2 June 2011|url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110205143222/http://www.londoncouncils.gov.uk/aboutus/organisation/leadingmembers/stevereed.htm |archive-date=5 February 2011 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n* Chairman of Central London Forward, a lobbying group representing five inner-London boroughs;<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.centrallondonforward.gov.uk/|title=Central London Forward|publisher=Central London Forward (CLF)}}{{failed verification|date=January 2020}}</ref>\n* A board member representing London's boroughs on the London Enterprise Partnership;<ref>[http://www.london.gov.uk/media/press_releases_mayoral/london-mayor-boroughs-and-business-create-partnership-growth Mayor of London]{{deadlink|date=January 2020}}</ref>\n* Co-Chair of the Vauxhall-Nine Elms-Battersea regeneration board;<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.london.gov.uk/who-runs-london/mayor/publications/planning/vauxhall-nine-elms-battersea-opportunity-area-planning-framework |title=Vauxhall Nine Elms Battersea Opportunity Area Planning Framework |access-date=2 June 2011|url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110626053302/http://london.gov.uk/who-runs-london/mayor/publications/planning/vauxhall-nine-elms-battersea-opportunity-area-planning-framework |archive-date=26 June 2011 |df=dmy-all|date=1 November 2009}}{{failed verification|date=January 2020}}</ref>\n* Chairman of the London Young People's Education and Skills Board<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.londoncouncils.gov.uk/policylobbying/children/education14to19/default.htm?showpage=-1 |title=14-19 Young People's Education and Skills - About us|access-date=2 June 2011|url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120310053724/http://www.londoncouncils.gov.uk/policylobbying/children/education14to19/default.htm?showpage=-1 |archive-date=10 March 2012 |df=dmy-all|publisher=London Councils }}</ref>\n* Served as a member of the London Board of the Homes and Communities Agency between 2009\u201311<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.homesandcommunities.co.uk/the-HCA-london-board |title=The HCA London Board|publisher=Homes and Communities Agency|date=2 August 2010 |access-date=20 June 2010|url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100929053722/http://www.homesandcommunities.co.uk/the-HCA-london-board |archive-date=29 September 2010 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nIn May 2010, Reed launched a consultation on plans to turn Lambeth into the country's first co-operative council<ref>{{cite news |title=Lambeth Council plans to be a cooperative  |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/england/london/8522105.stm |publisher=BBC News |date=18 February 2010 |accessdate=28 May 2010 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Council moves to tackle violent crime |url=https://www.theguardian.com/society/2008/jul/30/youngpeople.youthjustice |work=The Guardian |date= 30 July 2008|accessdate=28 May 2010 |first=Mary | last=O'Hara}}</ref> intending to deliver better services more cost-effectively by giving more control to communities and service users, reported in ''[[The Guardian]]'' newspaper as a possible new model for Labour in local government.<ref>{{cite news |title=Labour to rebrand Lambeth as 'John Lewis' council|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2010/feb/17/labour-rebrand-lambeth-john-lewis-council |work=The Guardian |date= 17 February 2010|accessdate=28 May 2010 | first=Allegra | last=Stratton}} {{registration}}</ref> The final report of Lambeth Council's Cooperative Council Commission<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.lambeth.gov.uk/Services/CouncilDemocracy/MakingADifference/TheCooperativeCouncil/?WT.mc_id=cooperativecouncil |title=Lambeth: The cooperative council|publisher=Lambeth Council|access-date=2 June 2011 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111224183132/http://www.lambeth.gov.uk/Services/CouncilDemocracy/MakingADifference/TheCooperativeCouncil/?WT.mc_id=cooperativecouncil |archive-date=24 December 2011 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> laid out the plans for achieving this objective and Lambeth Council put a transformation plan into effect.\n\nReed was reported to the Standards Board by a Conservative councillor after he disclosed that she was barred from voting on financial matters because of her refusal to pay council tax on one of her properties for several years.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.streathamguardian.co.uk/news/8378040.Council_leader_to_face_full_misconduct_hearing/ |title=Lambeth Council leader Steve Reed to face misconduct hearing|date=8 September 2010|work=Streatham Guardian}}{{deadlink|date=January 2020}}</ref> This information was legally disclosable and no sanction was imposed.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.lambeth.gov.uk/moderngov/ieDecisionDetails.aspx?AIId=13507 |title=Decision - Complaint 02/09-10: Councillor Steve Reed|publisher= Lambeth Council|date=10 March 2011 |accessdate=10 June 2017}}</ref>\n\nReed was named one of the three most influential council leaders in the country by the ''[[Local Government Chronicle]]'' in 2011<ref>{{cite web|work=Local Government Chronicle|title= 'LGC 50' 2011|url=http://www.lgcplus.com/news/lgc50/|publisher=EMap Publishing}} {{registration}}</ref> and was the highest-ranked Labour politician in the 2010 Pink List compiled by ''The Independent on Sunday''.<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/people/news/the-iiosi-pink-list-2010-2040472.html| work=The Independent | date=1 August 2010 | title=The ''IoS'' Pink List 2010}}</ref>\n\nReed was appointed [[Order of the British Empire|Officer of the Order of the British Empire]] (OBE) in the [[2013 Birthday Honours]] for services to local government.<ref>{{London Gazette |issue=60534 |date=15 June 2013 |page=12 |supp=y}}</ref>\n\n==Member of Parliament==\nReed's first attempt to enter Parliament was in Lambeth, contesting the Labour nomination for the [[Streatham (UK Parliament constituency)|Streatham constituency]] in 2008, on the retirement of [[Keith Hill (politician)|Keith Hill]]. In March of that year, Reed was beaten to the nomination by [[Chuka Umunna]]. On 3 November 2012, Reed narrowly defeated former Croydon Council leader [[Val Shawcross]] by only three votes,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.brixtonblog.com/steve-reed-wins-labour-selection-for-croydon-north/8002 |title=Steve Reed wins Labour selection for Croydon North |work=Brixton Blog|author=Kaye Wiggins |date=3 November 2012|publisher=Brixton Media |accessdate=10 June 2017}}</ref> to become the Labour candidate for the historically safe Labour seat of [[Croydon North (UK Parliament constituency)|Croydon North]], following a selection meeting of the local Croydon North Constituency Labour Party.<ref>{{cite news | url=http://www.thisiscroydontoday.co.uk/Breaking-Steve-Reed-selected-Labour-candidate/story-17223500-detail/story.html | archive-url=https://archive.is/20130114030656/http://www.thisiscroydontoday.co.uk/Breaking-Steve-Reed-selected-Labour-candidate/story-17223500-detail/story.html | url-status=dead | archive-date=14 January 2013 | title=Steve Reed selected as Labour candidate for Croydon North by-election | work=Croydon Advertiser | date=3 November 2012 }}</ref> The [[2012 Croydon North by-election|by-election]] followed on from the death of the former MP for Croydon North [[Malcolm Wicks]] and was won by Reed on 29 November 2012.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-london-20544539|title=Croydon North by-election: Labour's Steve Reed secures win|date=30 November 2012|publisher=BBC News|accessdate=14 January 2020}}</ref>\n\nIn October 2013 Reed was appointed a Shadow Home Office Minister by Labour Leader [[Ed Miliband]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://labourlist.org/2013/10/confirmed-labours-new-frontbench-team-in-full/|title=Confirmed: Labour's new frontbench team in full| date=8 October 2013|publisher=LabourList|accessdate=12 June 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn the [[2015 United Kingdom general election|2015 general election]], Reed again stood for the Croydon North constituency. He was elected as MP with 33,513 votes (a 62.5% share, up 6.6% from the previous General Election in 2010) and a majority of 21,364 (39.9%) with a 62.3% turnout.<ref name=\"bbc-2015-election\"/>\n\nOn 27 June 2016, Reed resigned as Shadow Minister for Local Government as part of the mass resignation of the Labour Shadow Cabinet against Jeremy Corbyn's leadership of the Labour party.<ref>{{cite tweet|user=SteveReedMP|author=Steve Reed|number=747333864486404097|date=27 June 2016|title=I have resigned as Shadow Minister for Local Government. Here is my letter of resignation}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/0/labour-shadow-cabinet-resignations---the-letters-in-full/|title=Labour shadow cabinet and ministers resignations - the letters in full|access-date=25 July 2016|work=The Telegraph|date=27 June 2016}}</ref> He supported [[Owen Smith]] in the [[2016 Labour Party (UK) leadership election|2016 Labour leadership election]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.mirror.co.uk/news/uk-news/mps-nominating-owen-smith-labour-8451186|title=Which MPs are nominating Owen Smith in the Labour leadership contest?|last1=Smith|first1=Mikey|date=20 July 2016|work=Mirror Online|access-date=10 November 2018|last2=Bloom|first2=Dan}}</ref>\n\nIn June 2018 Reed attempted to get a bill through parliament to make hospitals reveal details about how and when they use physical force against patients. Hospital staff would also under the bill get training about the possibility of unconscious bias against minority groups like young black men with mental health problems. Reed notes the death of his constituent, Olaseni Lewis, who died aged 23 during [[Bethlem Royal Hospital#Fatal restraints|use of restraint at Bethlem hospital]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.stevereedmp.co.uk/steve-launches-senis-law-to-protect-mental-health-patients/|title= Steve launches Seni's Law to protect mental health patients|publisher=Steve Reed MP|date=21 July 2017|author=Steve Reed}}</ref> A [[filibuster]] by [[Philip Davies]] prevented the bill succeeding.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://inews.co.uk/news/politics/conservative-mp-blocks-new-law-to-control-use-of-force-in-mental-health-units-by-speaking-for-almost-three-hours/|title=Conservative MP blocks new law to control use of force in mental health units by speaking for almost three hours|work= i News|date=15 July 2018}}</ref> Reed's bill was passed on 6 July 2018; it requires that police attending mental hospitals to apply restraints to wear body cameras.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/law/2018/jul/06/olaseni-lewis-mother-urges-mps-to-pass-filibustered-mental-health-bill|author=Dan Sabbagh|title= MPs pass mental health restraint bill after filibuster fears|work=The Guardian|date=6 July 2018}} {{registration}}</ref>\n\nReed noted flammable cladding involved in the [[Grenfell Tower fire]]. Reed stated, \"You ([[James Brokenshire]]) have not yet gone far enough to guarantee public safety. We urge you to reconsider and extend the scope of the ban on flammable cladding so everyone in our country can be reassured the buildings they use are safe from fire.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/uk-news/2018/nov/27/government-to-review-safety-advice-amid-new-high-rise-cladding-fears-grenfell|title= Government to review safety advice amid new high-rise cladding fears|author=Robert Booth|work=The Guardian|date=27 November 2018}} {{registration}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.stevereedmp.co.uk Steve Reed MP] Personal website\n*{{UK MP links | parliament = mr-steve-reed/4268 | publicwhip = Steve_Reed | theywork = steve_reed }}\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20100516064339/http://www.lambeth.gov.uk/moderngov/mgUserInfo.aspx?UID=134 Councillor Steve Reed], Lambeth Council (Archived)\n*[https://www.theguardian.com/profile/steve-reed Steve Reed] The Guardian\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-par|uk}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Malcolm Wicks]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|Member of Parliament]]<br />for [[Croydon North (UK Parliament constituency)|Croydon North]]|years=[[2012 Croydon North by-election|2012]]\u2013present}}\n{{s-inc}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{UK Shadow Cabinet}}\n{{London Labour Party MPs}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Reed, Steve}}\n[[Category:Councillors in the London Borough of Lambeth]]\n[[Category:Labour Party (UK) councillors]]\n[[Category:1963 births]]\n[[Category:Alumni of the University of Sheffield]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Gay politicians]]\n[[Category:LGBT members of the Parliament of the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:LGBT politicians from England]]\n[[Category:Officers of the Order of the British Empire]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 2010\u20132015]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 2015\u20132017]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 2017\u20132019]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 2019\u2013]]\n[[Category:Labour Party (UK) MPs for English constituencies]]\n[[Category:Leaders of local authorities of England]]\n", "text_old": "{{other people||Steve Reed (disambiguation)}}\n{{Short description|British politician and Member of Parliament  for Croydon North}}\n{{EngvarB|date=May 2015}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=June 2017}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| honorific-prefix = \n| name = Steve Reed\n| honorific-suffix = [[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|MP]] [[OBE]]\n| image = Official portrait of Mr Steve Reed crop 2.jpg\n| office = [[Shadow Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government]]\n| leader = [[Sir Keir Starmer]]\n| predecessor = [[Andrew Gwynne]]\n| successor = \n| term_start = 6 April 2020\n| term_end =\n| office1 = [[Department for Education|Shadow Minister for Children and Families]]\n| leader1 = [[Jeremy Corbyn]]\n| term_start1 = 24 June 2019\n| term_end1 = 6 April 2020\n| predecessor1 = [[Emma Lewell-Buck]]\n| successor1 = [[Tulip Siddiq]]\n| office2  = [[Department for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport|Shadow Minister for Civil Society]]\n| leader2  = [[Jeremy Corbyn]]\n| term_start2 = 3 October 2016\n| term_end2  = 24 June 2019\n| predecessor2 = [[Ian Lavery]]\n| successor2 = [[Vicky Foxcroft]]\n| office3 = [[Ministry of Housing, Communities and Local Government|Shadow Minister for Local Government]]\n| leader3 = [[Harriet Harman]] <small>''(Acting)''</small> <br> [[Jeremy Corbyn]]\n| term_start3 = 8 May 2015\n| term_end3  = 27 June 2016\n| predecessor3 = [[Andy Sawford]]\n| successor3  = [[Jim McMahon]]\n| office4  = [[Home Office|Shadow Home Office Minister]]\n| leader4  = [[Ed Miliband]]\n| term_start4 = 7 October 2013\n| term_end4   = 8 May 2015\n| predecessor4 = [[Gloria de Piero]]\n| successor4 = [[Lyn Brown]]\n| office5 = [[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|Member of Parliament]] <br /> for [[Croydon North (UK Parliament constituency)|Croydon North]]\n| term_start5 = 29 November 2012\n| term_end5 = \n| majority5 = 24,673 (44.3%)<ref name=\"bbc-2015-election\">{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/politics/constituencies/E14000655|title=Croydon North parliamentary constituency \u2013 Election 2015|publisher=BBC News|date=8 May 2015|accessdate=11 May 2015}}</ref>\n| predecessor5 = [[Malcolm Wicks]]\n| successor5 = \n| office6 = [[Lambeth London Borough Council|Leader of Lambeth Council]]\n| deputy6 = Jackie Meldrum\n| term_start6 = 4 May 2006\n| term_end6 = 29 November 2012\n| predecessor6 = Peter Truesdale\n| successor6 = Lib Peck\n| birth_name = Steven Mark Ward Reed\n| birth_date = {{Birth date and age|df=yes|1963|11|12}}\n| birth_place = [[St Albans]], [[Hertfordshire]], England\n| death_date = \n| death_place = \n| nationality = British\n| spouse = \n| party = [[Labour and Co-operative]]\n| relations = \n| children = \n| residence = \n| alma_mater = [[University of Sheffield]]\n| occupation = \n| profession = \n| signature = \n| website = [http://www.stevereedmp.co.uk SteveReedMP.co.uk]\n| footnotes = \n}}\n\n'''Steven Mark Ward Reed''' {{Post-nominals|country=GBR|size=100%|OBE}} (born 12 November 1963) is a British [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour]] and [[Co-operative Party]] politician who has been the [[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|Member of Parliament]] (MP) for [[Croydon North (UK Parliament constituency)|Croydon North]] since [[2012 Croydon North by-election|2012]]. He was previously the [[Lambeth Council|Leader of Lambeth Council]] from 2006 to 2012.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.lambeth.gov.uk/moderngov/mgUserInfo.aspx?UID%3D134|title=Committee details - Councillor Steve Reed|access-date=20 June 2010 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100516064339/http://www.lambeth.gov.uk/moderngov/mgUserInfo.aspx?UID=134 |archive-date=16 May 2010 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://labourlist.org/2012/11/steve-reed-selected-as-labours-candidate-in-croydon-north/ |title=Steve Reed selected as Labour's candidate in Croydon North |publisher=LabourList |date=3 November 2012 |accessdate=10 June 2017}}</ref> Reed does not hold responsibilities for [[Housing in England]], as [[Thangham Debbonaire]] serves as [[Shadow Secretary of State for Housing]], as if Labour form the next government, they will create a separate [[government department]] for housing.\n\n==Early life==\nReed was born and raised in [[St Albans]], [[Hertfordshire]], and his family worked at [[Odhams]] printing factory in [[Watford]] until it closed down in 1983.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.freebmd.org.uk/cgi/information.pl?cite=TpITzPC61DGIG7OxE0mkvg&scan=1|title=Reed Steven MW|accessdate=26 February 2018|work=FreeBMD|publisher=ONS}}</ref><ref name=\"CroydonNorth\">{{cite news|author=Gareth Davies |url=http://www.thisiscroydontoday.co.uk/Steve-Reed-favourite-Croydon-North-Lambeth/story-17426335-detail/story.html |title=Steve Reed: A favourite in Croydon North but not in Lambeth?|work=Croydon Advertiser |publisher=Local World|via=This is Croydon Today|date=26 November 2012 |accessdate=10 June 2017}}{{deadlink|date=January 2020}}</ref> Around this time, he joined the Labour Party before going on to study English at [[Sheffield University]].<ref name=\"CroydonNorth\" /> He worked in the educational publishing industry from 1990 to 2008.<ref name=\"CroydonNorth\" />\n\nIn March 2008 he narrowly lost out to [[Chuka Umunna]] for selection as Labour's 2010 election candidate for the [[Streatham (UK Parliament constituency)|Streatham constituency]].\n\n==Lambeth Council==\nReed first stood for the [[Lambeth London Borough Council]] in the [[1998 Lambeth Council election|1998 election]] and won the Town Hall ward (now [[Brixton Hill]]). In [[2002 Lambeth Council election|2002]] Labour lost control of Lambeth council to a Conservative/Liberal Democrat coalition, and in response, Reed was elected leader of the opposition.\n\nAfter Labour won back control of [[Lambeth Council]] in [[2006 Lambeth Council election|2006]], Reed was appointed the council's leader. During his tenure, Lambeth went from being rated London's worst-run borough, with a one-star rating in the [[Audit Commission (United Kingdom)|Audit Commission]]'s annual inspection in 2006, to having a three-star rating in 2009.<ref>{{cite news|publisher=ESI Media|url=https://www.standard.co.uk/news/lambeth-is-londons-worstrun-borough-7213025.html|title=Lambeth is London's worst-run borough|author=Ross Lydall|work=Evening Standard|date=22 February 2007}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://cpa.audit-commission.gov.uk/STCCScorecard.aspx?taxid=104598 |title=London Borough of Lambeth Comprehensive Performance Assessment (CPA) scorecard 2008|access-date=20 June 2010|url-status=dead |archive-url=http://webarchive.nationalarchives.gov.uk/20090414003855/http%3A//cpa.audit%2Dcommission.gov.uk/STCCScorecard.aspx?TaxID%3D104598 |archive-date=14 April 2009 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> At the [[2010 Lambeth Council election|2010 election]], Labour gained seats from the [[Liberal Democrats (UK)|Liberal Democrats]] and [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservatives]], making it the first time that Labour had been re-elected to lead in Lambeth for twenty years.\n\nReed held a number of significant positions in local government. He was:\n\n* Deputy Leader of Local Government Labour, an association representing Labour councillors nationally;<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.labourgroup.lga.gov.uk/lga/core/page.do?pageId=1828919|title=Labour Group Officers |access-date=14 January 2020|url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101012114836/http://www.labourgroup.lga.gov.uk/lga/core/page.do?pageId=1828919 |archive-date=12 October 2010 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n* Deputy Chairman of the Local Government Association;<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.lga.gov.uk/lga/councillor/profile-display.do?id=1716688|title=Cllr Steve Reed - Deputy Chair, LGA|publisher=Local Government Association|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110928072239/http://www.lga.gov.uk/lga/councillor/profile-display.do?id=1716688|archive-date=28 September 2011|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n* London Councils board member for Children's Services and Employment;<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.londoncouncils.gov.uk/aboutus/organisation/leadingmembers/stevereed.htm |title=Cllr Steve Reed - Executive member for children's services and skills and employment (Labour) |access-date=2 June 2011|url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110205143222/http://www.londoncouncils.gov.uk/aboutus/organisation/leadingmembers/stevereed.htm |archive-date=5 February 2011 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n* Chairman of Central London Forward, a lobbying group representing five inner-London boroughs;<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.centrallondonforward.gov.uk/|title=Central London Forward|publisher=Central London Forward (CLF)}}{{failed verification|date=January 2020}}</ref>\n* A board member representing London's boroughs on the London Enterprise Partnership;<ref>[http://www.london.gov.uk/media/press_releases_mayoral/london-mayor-boroughs-and-business-create-partnership-growth Mayor of London]{{deadlink|date=January 2020}}</ref>\n* Co-Chair of the Vauxhall-Nine Elms-Battersea regeneration board;<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.london.gov.uk/who-runs-london/mayor/publications/planning/vauxhall-nine-elms-battersea-opportunity-area-planning-framework |title=Vauxhall Nine Elms Battersea Opportunity Area Planning Framework |access-date=2 June 2011|url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110626053302/http://london.gov.uk/who-runs-london/mayor/publications/planning/vauxhall-nine-elms-battersea-opportunity-area-planning-framework |archive-date=26 June 2011 |df=dmy-all|date=1 November 2009}}{{failed verification|date=January 2020}}</ref>\n* Chairman of the London Young People's Education and Skills Board<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.londoncouncils.gov.uk/policylobbying/children/education14to19/default.htm?showpage=-1 |title=14-19 Young People's Education and Skills - About us|access-date=2 June 2011|url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120310053724/http://www.londoncouncils.gov.uk/policylobbying/children/education14to19/default.htm?showpage=-1 |archive-date=10 March 2012 |df=dmy-all|publisher=London Councils }}</ref>\n* Served as a member of the London Board of the Homes and Communities Agency between 2009\u201311<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.homesandcommunities.co.uk/the-HCA-london-board |title=The HCA London Board|publisher=Homes and Communities Agency|date=2 August 2010 |access-date=20 June 2010|url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100929053722/http://www.homesandcommunities.co.uk/the-HCA-london-board |archive-date=29 September 2010 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nIn May 2010, Reed launched a consultation on plans to turn Lambeth into the country's first co-operative council<ref>{{cite news |title=Lambeth Council plans to be a cooperative  |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/england/london/8522105.stm |publisher=BBC News |date=18 February 2010 |accessdate=28 May 2010 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Council moves to tackle violent crime |url=https://www.theguardian.com/society/2008/jul/30/youngpeople.youthjustice |work=The Guardian |date= 30 July 2008|accessdate=28 May 2010 |first=Mary | last=O'Hara}}</ref> intending to deliver better services more cost-effectively by giving more control to communities and service users, reported in ''[[The Guardian]]'' newspaper as a possible new model for Labour in local government.<ref>{{cite news |title=Labour to rebrand Lambeth as 'John Lewis' council|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2010/feb/17/labour-rebrand-lambeth-john-lewis-council |work=The Guardian |date= 17 February 2010|accessdate=28 May 2010 | first=Allegra | last=Stratton}} {{registration}}</ref> The final report of Lambeth Council's Cooperative Council Commission<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.lambeth.gov.uk/Services/CouncilDemocracy/MakingADifference/TheCooperativeCouncil/?WT.mc_id=cooperativecouncil |title=Lambeth: The cooperative council|publisher=Lambeth Council|access-date=2 June 2011 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111224183132/http://www.lambeth.gov.uk/Services/CouncilDemocracy/MakingADifference/TheCooperativeCouncil/?WT.mc_id=cooperativecouncil |archive-date=24 December 2011 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> laid out the plans for achieving this objective and Lambeth Council put a transformation plan into effect.\n\nReed was reported to the Standards Board by a Conservative councillor after he disclosed that she was barred from voting on financial matters because of her refusal to pay council tax on one of her properties for several years.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.streathamguardian.co.uk/news/8378040.Council_leader_to_face_full_misconduct_hearing/ |title=Lambeth Council leader Steve Reed to face misconduct hearing|date=8 September 2010|work=Streatham Guardian}}{{deadlink|date=January 2020}}</ref> This information was legally disclosable and no sanction was imposed.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.lambeth.gov.uk/moderngov/ieDecisionDetails.aspx?AIId=13507 |title=Decision - Complaint 02/09-10: Councillor Steve Reed|publisher= Lambeth Council|date=10 March 2011 |accessdate=10 June 2017}}</ref>\n\nReed was named one of the three most influential council leaders in the country by the ''[[Local Government Chronicle]]'' in 2011<ref>{{cite web|work=Local Government Chronicle|title= 'LGC 50' 2011|url=http://www.lgcplus.com/news/lgc50/|publisher=EMap Publishing}} {{registration}}</ref> and was the highest-ranked Labour politician in the 2010 Pink List compiled by ''The Independent on Sunday''.<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/people/news/the-iiosi-pink-list-2010-2040472.html| work=The Independent | date=1 August 2010 | title=The ''IoS'' Pink List 2010}}</ref>\n\nReed was appointed [[Order of the British Empire|Officer of the Order of the British Empire]] (OBE) in the [[2013 Birthday Honours]] for services to local government.<ref>{{London Gazette |issue=60534 |date=15 June 2013 |page=12 |supp=y}}</ref>\n\n==Member of Parliament==\nReed's first attempt to enter Parliament was in Lambeth, contesting the Labour nomination for the [[Streatham (UK Parliament constituency)|Streatham constituency]] in 2008, on the retirement of [[Keith Hill (politician)|Keith Hill]]. In March of that year, Reed was beaten to the nomination by [[Chuka Umunna]]. On 3 November 2012, Reed narrowly defeated former Croydon Council leader [[Val Shawcross]] by only three votes,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.brixtonblog.com/steve-reed-wins-labour-selection-for-croydon-north/8002 |title=Steve Reed wins Labour selection for Croydon North |work=Brixton Blog|author=Kaye Wiggins |date=3 November 2012|publisher=Brixton Media |accessdate=10 June 2017}}</ref> to become the Labour candidate for the historically safe Labour seat of [[Croydon North (UK Parliament constituency)|Croydon North]], following a selection meeting of the local Croydon North Constituency Labour Party.<ref>{{cite news | url=http://www.thisiscroydontoday.co.uk/Breaking-Steve-Reed-selected-Labour-candidate/story-17223500-detail/story.html | archive-url=https://archive.is/20130114030656/http://www.thisiscroydontoday.co.uk/Breaking-Steve-Reed-selected-Labour-candidate/story-17223500-detail/story.html | url-status=dead | archive-date=14 January 2013 | title=Steve Reed selected as Labour candidate for Croydon North by-election | work=Croydon Advertiser | date=3 November 2012 }}</ref> The [[2012 Croydon North by-election|by-election]] followed on from the death of the former MP for Croydon North [[Malcolm Wicks]] and was won by Reed on 29 November 2012.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-london-20544539|title=Croydon North by-election: Labour's Steve Reed secures win|date=30 November 2012|publisher=BBC News|accessdate=14 January 2020}}</ref>\n\nIn October 2013 Reed was appointed a Shadow Home Office Minister by Labour Leader [[Ed Miliband]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://labourlist.org/2013/10/confirmed-labours-new-frontbench-team-in-full/|title=Confirmed: Labour's new frontbench team in full| date=8 October 2013|publisher=LabourList|accessdate=12 June 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn the [[2015 United Kingdom general election|2015 general election]], Reed again stood for the Croydon North constituency. He was elected as MP with 33,513 votes (a 62.5% share, up 6.6% from the previous General Election in 2010) and a majority of 21,364 (39.9%) with a 62.3% turnout.<ref name=\"bbc-2015-election\"/>\n\nOn 27 June 2016, Reed resigned as Shadow Minister for Local Government as part of the mass resignation of the Labour Shadow Cabinet against Jeremy Corbyn's leadership of the Labour party.<ref>{{cite tweet|user=SteveReedMP|author=Steve Reed|number=747333864486404097|date=27 June 2016|title=I have resigned as Shadow Minister for Local Government. Here is my letter of resignation}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/0/labour-shadow-cabinet-resignations---the-letters-in-full/|title=Labour shadow cabinet and ministers resignations - the letters in full|access-date=25 July 2016|work=The Telegraph|date=27 June 2016}}</ref> He supported [[Owen Smith]] in the [[2016 Labour Party (UK) leadership election|2016 Labour leadership election]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.mirror.co.uk/news/uk-news/mps-nominating-owen-smith-labour-8451186|title=Which MPs are nominating Owen Smith in the Labour leadership contest?|last1=Smith|first1=Mikey|date=20 July 2016|work=Mirror Online|access-date=10 November 2018|last2=Bloom|first2=Dan}}</ref>\n\nIn June 2018 Reed attempted to get a bill through parliament to make hospitals reveal details about how and when they use physical force against patients. Hospital staff would also under the bill get training about the possibility of unconscious bias against minority groups like young black men with mental health problems. Reed notes the death of his constituent, Olaseni Lewis, who died aged 23 during [[Bethlem Royal Hospital#Fatal restraints|use of restraint at Bethlem hospital]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.stevereedmp.co.uk/steve-launches-senis-law-to-protect-mental-health-patients/|title= Steve launches Seni's Law to protect mental health patients|publisher=Steve Reed MP|date=21 July 2017|author=Steve Reed}}</ref> A [[filibuster]] by [[Philip Davies]] prevented the bill succeeding.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://inews.co.uk/news/politics/conservative-mp-blocks-new-law-to-control-use-of-force-in-mental-health-units-by-speaking-for-almost-three-hours/|title=Conservative MP blocks new law to control use of force in mental health units by speaking for almost three hours|work= i News|date=15 July 2018}}</ref> Reed's bill was passed on 6 July 2018; it requires that police attending mental hospitals to apply restraints to wear body cameras.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/law/2018/jul/06/olaseni-lewis-mother-urges-mps-to-pass-filibustered-mental-health-bill|author=Dan Sabbagh|title= MPs pass mental health restraint bill after filibuster fears|work=The Guardian|date=6 July 2018}} {{registration}}</ref>\n\nReed noted flammable cladding involved in the [[Grenfell Tower fire]]. Reed stated, \"You ([[James Brokenshire]]) have not yet gone far enough to guarantee public safety. We urge you to reconsider and extend the scope of the ban on flammable cladding so everyone in our country can be reassured the buildings they use are safe from fire.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/uk-news/2018/nov/27/government-to-review-safety-advice-amid-new-high-rise-cladding-fears-grenfell|title= Government to review safety advice amid new high-rise cladding fears|author=Robert Booth|work=The Guardian|date=27 November 2018}} {{registration}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.stevereedmp.co.uk Steve Reed MP] Personal website\n*{{UK MP links | parliament = mr-steve-reed/4268 | publicwhip = Steve_Reed | theywork = steve_reed }}\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20100516064339/http://www.lambeth.gov.uk/moderngov/mgUserInfo.aspx?UID=134 Councillor Steve Reed], Lambeth Council (Archived)\n*[https://www.theguardian.com/profile/steve-reed Steve Reed] The Guardian\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-par|uk}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Malcolm Wicks]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|Member of Parliament]]<br />for [[Croydon North (UK Parliament constituency)|Croydon North]]|years=[[2012 Croydon North by-election|2012]]\u2013present}}\n{{s-inc}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{UK Shadow Cabinet}}\n{{London Labour Party MPs}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Reed, Steve}}\n[[Category:Councillors in the London Borough of Lambeth]]\n[[Category:Labour Party (UK) councillors]]\n[[Category:1963 births]]\n[[Category:Alumni of the University of Sheffield]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Gay politicians]]\n[[Category:LGBT members of the Parliament of the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:LGBT politicians from England]]\n[[Category:Officers of the Order of the British Empire]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 2010\u20132015]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 2015\u20132017]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 2017\u20132019]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 2019\u2013]]\n[[Category:Labour Party (UK) MPs for English constituencies]]\n[[Category:Leaders of local authorities of England]]\n", "name_user": "JLo-Watson", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Steve_Reed_(politician)"}
{"title_page": "Janice Perry", "text_new": "{{about||the composer|Janice Kapp Perry|the Los Angeles politician|Jan Perry}}\n{{Infobox artist\n| name          = Janice Perry\n| image         = \n| caption       = \n| birth_name    = \n| birth_date    =\n| birth_place   =\n| death_date    = \n| death_place   = \n| nationality   = \n| movement      = [[Feminist art]]\n| field         = [[Performance art]]\n| training      = [[Drew University]], [[Goddard College]]\n}}\n\n'''Janice Perry''' (also known as '''GAL''') is an American performance artist. Described as \"a cross between Doris Day and a high-velocity rifle\",<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/cambridgeshire/content/articles/2007/08/21/janice_perry_interview_feature.shtml|title=Out of the Box - or off her trolley?|last=BBC|website=www.bbc.co.uk|language=en-gb|access-date=2020-01-10}}</ref> her interdisciplinary work has been presented on stage, published, screened at film festivals, adapted for radio and television (NPR, PBS, BBC), and exhibited at academic and cultural institutions in the United States and Europe.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://discovery.nationalarchives.gov.uk/details/r/006d4dd1-bf55-480e-bc96-52ba1ca11e6e|title=Janice Perry aka 'Gal'|date=December 14, 1993|via=National Archive of the UK}}</ref><ref name=\"auto\">https://www.ici-berlin.org/events/janice-perry/</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://dai-heidelberg.de/de/veranstaltungen/mourning-derrida-3883/|title=Veranstaltungen - Deutsch-Amerikanisches Institut. Haus der Kultur.|website=DAI Deutsch|language=de-DE|access-date=2020-01-10}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.timesargus.com/janice-perry-is-a-hoot/article_0a6b2d30-648b-5f33-ae28-d9ecd2c49225.html|title=Janice Perry is a hoot|last=Writer|first=JIM LOWE Staff|website=Times Argus|language=en|access-date=2020-01-10}}</ref> Perry began international touring in 1981. <ref>http://www.centreforsoloperformance.com/workshops-events/janice-perry-not-just-another-pretty-face-a-retrospective/</ref>\n\nShe has received multiple fellowships for live performance, visual art, and teaching from the [[Fulbright Commission]]<ref name=\"auto1\">{{Cite web|url=https://books.google.com/?id=hfKSppSUyGIC&pg=PA78&lpg=PA78&dq=janice+perry+fulbright#v=onepage&q=janice+perry+fulbright&f=false|title=Directory of U.S. Fulbright Scholars|date=December 14, 2002|publisher=Council for International Exchange of Scholars|via=Google Books}}</ref>/[[United States Department of State|US Department of State]], the [[National Endowment for the Arts]], the Vermont Arts Council, the Vermont Community Foundation, and other organizations.  Her performance/installation, ''Being Derrida'',<ref name=\"auto\"/> was a semi-finalist in the Smithsonian Institution's [[National Portrait Gallery (United States)|National Portrait Gallery]] [[Outwin Boochever Portrait Competition]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://portraitcompetition.si.edu/|title=The Outwin: American Portraiture Today {{!}} Smithsonian's National Portrait Gallery|website=portraitcompetition.si.edu|access-date=2020-01-10}}</ref>\n\nPerry taught [[performance studies]] as a Fulbright professor<ref>{{Cite book|title=Directory of Fulbright Scholars|last=|first=|publisher=Council for International Exchange of Scholars, 2002|year=2002|isbn=|location=|pages=78}}</ref><ref name=\"auto1\"/> in [[American studies]] at [[Goethe University Frankfurt]], and the [[University of W\u00fcrzburg]] from 2001 to 2005; and at the [[University of Vermont]] in the English, theatre, art, and leadership and developmental sciences departments in association with the UVM [[gender studies]] program from 2006 to 2017.\n\nThroughout her career, Perry has led, or partnered on, international collaborations in multi-media, site responsive, video and live art performance,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://cultmtl.com/2013/05/memoirs-of-a-pole-dancer-philip-bussmann-montreal-video-art/|title=Memoirs of a Pole Dancer|first=Caia|last=Hagel|date=May 23, 2013|website=Cult MTL}}</ref> and more traditional stage work with groups of students,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.mdx.ac.uk/news/2014/12/janice-perry-gives-theatre-arts-students-exclusive-performance|title=Janice Perry gives Theatre Arts students exclusive performance {{!}} Middlesex University London|website=www.mdx.ac.uk|access-date=2020-01-10}}</ref> and emerging and established artists in the US, Europe, South Korea, and South Africa, researching performativity in intersectional identity, theoretical, social, and scientific concepts.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thepitchkc.com/nothing-is-sacred/|title=Nothing Is Sacred|date=2000-08-31|website=The Pitch |access-date=2020-01-10}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n<!-- Inline citations added to your article will automatically display here. See https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/WP:REFB for instructions on how to add citations. -->\n{{reflist}}\n*Lowe, Jim (February 10, 2008). [https://www.timesargus.com/janice-perry-is-a-hoot/article_0a6b2d30-648b-5f33-ae28-d9ecd2c49225.html \"Janice Perry is a hoot\"]. ''Times Argus''. \n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Perry, Janice}}\n[[Category:American performance artists]]\n[[Category:Feminist artists]]\n[[Category:1950 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n", "text_old": "{{For2|the composer|[[Janice Kapp Perry]]|the Los Angeles politician|[[Jan Perry]]}}\n{{Infobox artist\n| name          = Janice Perry\n| image         = \n| caption       = \n| birth_name    = \n| birth_date    =\n| birth_place   =\n| death_date    = \n| death_place   = \n| nationality   = \n| movement      = [[Feminist art]]\n| field         = [[Performance art]]\n| training      = [[Drew University]], [[Goddard College]]\n}}\n\n'''Janice Perry''' (also known as '''GAL''') is an American performance artist. Described as \"a cross between Doris Day and a high-velocity rifle\",<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/cambridgeshire/content/articles/2007/08/21/janice_perry_interview_feature.shtml|title=Out of the Box - or off her trolley?|last=BBC|website=