rtrait Gallery]] [[Outwin Boochever Portrait Competition]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://portraitcompetition.si.edu/|title=The Outwin: American Portraiture Today {{!}} Smithsonian's National Portrait Gallery|website=portraitcompetition.si.edu|access-date=2020-01-10}}</ref>\n\nPerry taught [[performance studies]] as a Fulbright professor<ref>{{Cite book|title=Directory of Fulbright Scholars|last=|first=|publisher=Council for International Exchange of Scholars, 2002|year=2002|isbn=|location=|pages=78}}</ref><ref name=\"auto1\"/> in [[American studies]] at [[Goethe University Frankfurt]], and the [[University of W\u00fcrzburg]] from 2001 to 2005; and at the [[University of Vermont]] in the English, theatre, art, and leadership and developmental sciences departments in association with the UVM [[gender studies]] program from 2006 to 2017.\n\nThroughout her career, Perry has led, or partnered on, international collaborations in multi-media, site responsive, video and live art performance,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://cultmtl.com/2013/05/memoirs-of-a-pole-dancer-philip-bussmann-montreal-video-art/|title=Memoirs of a Pole Dancer|first=Caia|last=Hagel|date=May 23, 2013|website=Cult MTL}}</ref> and more traditional stage work with groups of students,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.mdx.ac.uk/news/2014/12/janice-perry-gives-theatre-arts-students-exclusive-performance|title=Janice Perry gives Theatre Arts students exclusive performance {{!}} Middlesex University London|website=www.mdx.ac.uk|access-date=2020-01-10}}</ref> and emerging and established artists in the US, Europe, South Korea, and South Africa, researching performativity in intersectional identity, theoretical, social, and scientific concepts.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thepitchkc.com/nothing-is-sacred/|title=Nothing Is Sacred|date=2000-08-31|website=The Pitch |access-date=2020-01-10}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n<!-- Inline citations added to your article will automatically display here. See https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/WP:REFB for instructions on how to add citations. -->\n{{reflist}}\n*Lowe, Jim (February 10, 2008). [https://www.timesargus.com/janice-perry-is-a-hoot/article_0a6b2d30-648b-5f33-ae28-d9ecd2c49225.html \"Janice Perry is a hoot\"]. ''Times Argus''. \n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Perry, Janice}}\n[[Category:American performance artists]]\n[[Category:Feminist artists]]\n[[Category:1950 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n", "name_user": "Nihiltres", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200etop:Simplified hatnote syntax", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Janice_Perry"}
{"title_page": "Kaieteur Falls", "text_new": "{{Infobox waterfall\n| name = Kaieteur \n = [[Guyana]]\n| map_image = GUY_orthographic.svg\n| coords = {{coord|5|10|30|N|59|28|49.8|W|type:landmar_region:GY-PT|display=inline,title}}\n| elevation = <!-- {{convert|4380|m or ft|abbr=on}}-->\n| type = Plunge\n| height = 741 feet/226 metres\n| height_longest = 741 feet/226 metres\n| average_width = 371 feet/113 metres\n| number_drops = 1 (tallest single drop waterfall of the world)\n| average_flow = 660 m\u00b3/s\n| watercourse = [[Potaro River]]\n| world_rank = 123\n}}\n\n'''Kaieteur Falls''' is the world's largest single drop [[waterfall]] by the volume of water flowing over it.  Located on the [[Potaro River]] in the [[Kaieteur National Park]], it sits in a section of the [[Amazon rainforest]] included in the [[Potaro-Siparuni]] region of [[Guyana]].  It is 226 metres (741&nbsp;ft) high when measured from its plunge over a [[sandstone]] and [[Conglomerate (geology)|conglomerate]] cliff to the first break. It then flows over a series of steep cascades that, when included in the measurements, bring the total height to 251 metres (822&nbsp;ft). While many falls have greater height, few have the combination of height and water volume, and Kaieteur is among the most powerful waterfalls in the world with an average flow rate of 663 cubic metres per second (23,400 cubic feet per second).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.world-waterfalls.com/waterfall.php?num=151|title=Kaieteur Falls  -  World Waterfall Database|publisher=|access-date=2008-12-02|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171010062927/http://www.world-waterfalls.com/waterfall.php?num=151|archive-date=2017-10-10|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nKaieteur Falls is about four times higher than [[Niagara Falls]], on the border between [[Canada]] and the [[United States]], and about twice the height of [[Victoria Falls, Zambia|Victoria Falls]], on the border of [[Zambia]] and [[Zimbabwe]] in [[Africa]].  It is a single drop waterfall.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.worldwaterfalldatabase.com/waterfall/Kaieteur-Falls-114/|title=Kaieteur Falls  -  World Waterfall Database|publisher=}}</ref>\n\nUpriver from the falls, the [[Potaro Plateau]] stretches out to the distant [[escarpment]] of the [[Pakaraima Mountains]].  The Potaro River empties into the [[Essequibo River]] which is one of the longest and widest rivers in South America and the longest river in Guyana.\n\n== History and discovery ==\nThe falls were rediscovered by Europeans in 1870 by a party led by [[Charles Barrington Brown]], a British geologist appointed as a government surveyor to the colony of [[British Guiana]].  Brown and his partner [[James Sawkins]] had arrived in [[Georgetown, Guyana|Georgetown]] in 1867, and while they did some of their mapping and preparation of geological reports together, some work was performed in separate expeditions, and Sawkins was taking a break from his work at the time of Brown's discovery of Kaieteur.  At this point, Brown did not have time to investigate Kaieteur Falls closer, so he returned one year later to make comprehensive measurements.\n\nBrown\u2019s book ''Canoe and Camp life in British Guiana'' was published in 1876. Two years later, in 1878, he published ''Fifteen Thousand Miles on the Amazon and its tributaries''.\n\nAccording to a [[Patamona]] Indian legend, Kaieteur Falls was named for Kai, a chief, or [[Toshao]] who acted to save his people by paddling over the falls in an act of self-sacrifice to [[Makonaima]], the great spirit.\n\nAnother legend though was told to Brown by Amerindians in the night of discovery of falls: Kaieteur has been named after an unpleasant old man who was placed in a boat and shoved in the fall by his relatives. Thus the fall was named \"Kaieteur\", which means \"old-man-fall\".\n\n== Tourism ==\nKaieteur Falls is a major tourist attraction in Guyana. It is in Kaieteur National Park in the center of Guyana's rainforest.\n\nThe park is served by [[Kaieteur International Airport]], about a 15-minute walk from the top of Kaieteur falls, with frequent flights to [[Ogle Airport]] and [[Cheddi Jagan International Airport]] in Georgetown.\n\n==Popular culture==\nKaieteur Falls is featured in:\n\n* the documentary film ''[[The White Diamond]]'' by [[Werner Herzog]] and Animal Planet's ''[[River Monsters]]'' with [[Jeremy Wade]].\n* the science fiction animation television series ''[[G Gundam]]''. The lead character trains and bathes under the falls before his final fight.\n* the opening of the fourth season credits of the Discovery Channel's series \"Gold Rush\" (2013). It also features in the body of a few episodes of that season.\n* episode 6 of [[David Attenborough]]'s series ''[[Life on Earth (TV series)|Life on Earth]]'' in which the native frogs, which thrive in the moist conditions, are discussed.\n* episode 1 of [[Steve Backshall]]'s series ''[[Deadly (UK TV series)#Backshall.27s Deadly Adventures|Deadly Adventures]]'' where Steve abseils to the bottom and camps overnight.\n\n==Gallery==\n<gallery mode=packed>\nImage:Kaiteur September 2007.JPG|Kaieteur Falls September 2007\nImage:Kaieteur Falls Guyana (2) 2007.jpg|Kaietur Falls in the Dry Season, Feb 2007\nFile:Kaieteur-falls.JPG\nFile:Kaieteur Falls.JPG\nFile:Kaieteur Falls pose longue.jpg\n</gallery>\n\n==See Also==\n*[[List of waterfalls by flow rate]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{commons category}}\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20070109120418/http://www.kaieteurpark.gov.gy/ Kaieteur National Park] home to the Kaieteur Falls.\n*[http://www.world-of-waterfalls.com/latin-america-kaieteur-falls.html Kaieteur Falls]\n*[http://www.beautifulworld.com/south-america/guyana/kaieteur-falls Kaieteur Falls] at Beautiful World\n\n[[Category:Waterfalls of Guyana]]\n[[Category:Potaro-Siparuni]]\n[[Category:Tourist attractions in Guyana]]\n[[Category:Geological type localities]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox waterfall\n| name = Kaieteur Falls\n| photo = GuyanaKaieteurFalls2004.jpg\n| photo_caption = Kaieteur Falls, [[Guyana]], in rainy season 2004\n| location = [[Guyana]]\n| map_image = GUY_orthographic.svg\n| coords = {{coord|5|10|30|N|59|28|49.8|W|type:landmar_region:GY-PT|display=inline,title}}\n| elevation = <!-- {{convert|4380|m or ft|abbr=on}}-->\n| type = Plunge\n| height = 741 feet/226 metres\n| height_longest = 741 feet/226 metres\n| average_width = 371 feet/113 metres\n| number_drops = 1 (tallest single drop waterfall of the world)\n| average_flow = 660 m\u00b3/s\n| watercourse = [[Potaro River]]\n| world_rank = 123\n}}\n\n'''Kaieteur Falls''' is the world's largest single drop [[waterfall]] by the volume of water flowing over it.  Located on the [[Potaro River]] in the [[Kaieteur National Park]], it sits in a section of the [[Amazon rainforest]] included in the [[Potaro-Siparuni]] region of [[Guyana]].  It is 226 metres (741&nbsp;ft) high when measured from its plunge over a [[sandstone]] and [[Conglomerate (geology)|conglomerate]] cliff to the first break. It then flows over a series of steep cascades that, when included in the measurements, bring the total height to 251 metres (822&nbsp;ft). While many falls have greater height, few have the combination of height and water volume, and Kaieteur is among the most powerful waterfalls in the world with an average flow rate of 663 cubic metres per second (23,400 cubic feet per second).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.world-waterfalls.com/waterfall.php?num=151|title=Kaieteur Falls  -  World Waterfall Database|publisher=|access-date=2008-12-02|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171010062927/http://www.world-waterfalls.com/waterfall.php?num=151|archive-date=2017-10-10|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nKaieteur Falls is about four times higher than [[Niagara Falls]], on the border between [[Canada]] and the [[United States]], and about twice the height of [[Victoria Falls, Zambia|Victoria Falls]], on the border of [[Zambia]] and [[Zimbabwe]] in [[Africa]].  It is a single drop waterfall.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.worldwaterfalldatabase.com/waterfall/Kaieteur-Falls-114/|title=Kaieteur Falls  -  World Waterfall Database|publisher=}}</ref>\n\nUpriver from the falls, the [[Potaro Plateau]] stretches out to the distant [[escarpment]] of the [[Pakaraima Mountains]].  The Potaro River empties into the [[Essequibo River]] which is one of the longest and widest rivers in South America and the longest river in Guyana.\n\n== History and discovery ==\nThe falls were rediscovered by Europeans in 1870 by a party led by [[Charles Barrington Brown]], a British geologist appointed as a government surveyor to the colony of [[British Guiana]].  Brown and his partner [[James Sawkins]] had arrived in [[Georgetown, Guyana|Georgetown]] in 1867, and while they did some of their mapping and preparation of geological reports together, some work was performed in separate expeditions, and Sawkins was taking a break from his work at the time of Brown's discovery of Kaieteur.  At this point, Brown did not have time to investigate Kaieteur Falls closer, so he returned one year later to make comprehensive measurements.\n\nBrown\u2019s book ''Canoe and Camp life in British Guiana'' was published in 1876. Two years later, in 1878, he published ''Fifteen Thousand Miles on the Amazon and its tributaries''.\n\nAccording to a [[Patamona]] Indian legend, Kaieteur Falls was named for Kai, a chief, or [[Toshao]] who acted to save his people by paddling over the falls in an act of self-sacrifice to [[Makonaima]], the great spirit.\n\nAnother legend though was told to Brown by Amerindians in the night of discovery of falls: Kaieteur has been named after an unpleasant old man who was placed in a boat and shoved in the fall by his relatives. Thus the fall was named \"Kaieteur\", which means \"old-man-fall\".\n\n== Tourism ==\nKaieteur Falls is a major tourist attraction in Guyana. It is in Kaieteur National Park in the center of Guyana's rainforest.\n\nThe park is served by [[Kaieteur International Airport]], about a 15-minute walk from the top of Kaieteur falls, with frequent flights to [[Ogle Airport]] and [[Cheddi Jagan International Airport]] in Georgetown.\n\n==Popular culture==\nKaieteur Falls is featured in:\n\n* the documentary film ''[[The White Diamond]]'' by [[Werner Herzog]] and Animal Planet's ''[[River Monsters]]'' with [[Jeremy Wade]].\n* the science fiction animation television series ''[[G Gundam]]''. The lead character trains and bathes under the falls before his final fight.\n* the opening of the fourth season credits of the Discovery Channel's series \"Gold Rush\" (2013). It also features in the body of a few episodes of that season.\n* episode 6 of [[David Attenborough]]'s series ''[[Life on Earth (TV series)|Life on Earth]]'' in which the native frogs, which thrive in the moist conditions, are discussed.\n* episode 1 of [[Steve Backshall]]'s series ''[[Deadly (UK TV series)#Backshall.27s Deadly Adventures|Deadly Adventures]]'' where Steve abseils to the bottom and camps overnight.\n\n==Gallery==\n<gallery mode=packed>\nImage:Kaiteur September 2007.JPG|Kaieteur Falls September 2007\nImage:Kaieteur Falls Guyana (2) 2007.jpg|Kaietur Falls in the Dry Season, Feb 2007\nFile:Kaieteur-falls.JPG\nFile:Kaieteur Falls.JPG\nFile:Kaieteur Falls pose longue.jpg\n</gallery>\n\n==See Also==\n*[[List of waterfalls by flow rate]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{commons category}}\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20070109120418/http://www.kaieteurpark.gov.gy/ Kaieteur National Park] home to the Kaieteur Falls.\n*[http://www.world-of-waterfalls.com/latin-america-kaieteur-falls.html Kaieteur Falls]\n*[http://www.beautifulworld.com/south-america/guyana/kaieteur-falls Kaieteur Falls] at Beautiful World\n\n[[Category:Waterfalls of Guyana]]\n[[Category:Potaro-Siparuni]]\n[[Category:Tourist attractions in Guyana]]\n[[Category:Geological type localities]]\n", "name_user": "2a02:c7f:ae58:2700:e55c:8862: