{"title_page": "Janice Kapp Perry", "text_new": "{{about||the performance artist|Janice Perry|the Los Angeles politician|Jan Perry}}\n\n[[File:JKP head crop.jpg|thumb|Janice Kapp Perry in 2019]]\n'''Janice Kapp Perry''' (born 1938) is a composer, songwriter, and author. She is most notable for her work related to her membership in [[The Church of Jesus Christ of Latter-day Saints]] (LDS Church). She has written over 1,200 songs, which appear in the church's [[Hymns of The Church of Jesus Christ of Latter-day Saints (1985 book)|official hymnal]], ''[[Children's Songbook]]'', and many personal albums, songbooks, and musicals. Perry has also composed albums in Spanish, Portuguese, Chinese, Japanese, and Korean.\n\n== Early life ==\nPerry was born on October 1, 1938 in [[Ogden, Utah]], and spent her childhood on a farm in [[Vale, Oregon]]. She grew up in a very musical family. Her mother, Ruth, played the piano and wrote musicals for the children to perform in the community. Her father, Jacob, learned to play the drums to accompany his wife in a family band.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://ldsmag.com/happy-birthday-to-janice-kapp-perry-looking-back-on-80-years/|title=Happy Birthday to Janice Kapp Perry: Looking Back on 80 Years!|website=LDS Magazine|access-date=2018-11-01}}</ref> After her father died, Perry played the drums in his place.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite news|url=https://magazine.byu.edu/article/a-testimony-through-song/|title=Janice Kapp Perry wrote over 160 hymns as a way to share her testimony|work=BYU Magazine|access-date=2018-11-01|language=en-US}}</ref> The children in the family also performed in a quartet.<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.deseretnews.com/article/900035128/mormon-songwriter-janice-kapp-perry-talks-new-hymn-book.html|title=Beloved church songwriter Janice Kapp Perry weighs in on the new hymn book|last=Robinson|first=Doug|date=2018-10-05|work=DeseretNews.com|access-date=2018-11-01|language=en}}</ref> In high school, she was in the band, playing snare drum and tympani.<ref name=\":7\">{{Cite book|title=Women of Character: Profiles of 100 Prominent LDS Women|last=Black|first=Susan Easton|last2=Woodger|first2=Mary Jane|publisher=Covenant Communications Inc.|year=2011|isbn=9781680470185|location=American Fork, Utah|pages=227\u2013229}}</ref> She also wrote her very first song, titled ''\"I Walked in God's Garden.\"''<ref name=\":1\" /> Though music was an important part of her childhood, Perry spent most of her time playing sports. She loved volleyball, basketball and even football.<ref name=\":7\" /> She especially loved softball.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\nPerry attended [[Brigham Young University]] (BYU) where she studied music composition and theory. While there, she played in BYU's concert band, orchestra<ref name=\":2\" /> and sang in the choir.<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite web|url=https://ldsmag.com/article-1-11618/|title=Thoughts from a Lifelong Choir Junkie|website=LDS Magazine|access-date=2018-11-01}}</ref>\n\n== Compositions ==\nAt the age of 38, Perry broke one of her ankles during one of her basketball games. Her television broke at the same time. With the extra time the incidents afforded her, she was assigned by her ward to compose music for their ward road show.<ref name=\":1\" /> She entered church song writing competitions and wrote new songs for her local church community.<ref name=\":4\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.deseretnews.com/article/600113781/Utahns-noted-for-great-notes.html|title=Utahn's noted for great notes|last=Robinson|first=Doug|date=2005-02-22|work=DeseretNews.com|access-date=2018-11-01|language=en}}</ref>\n\nPerry experimented with many styles at the beginning of her career, writing pop music that she sent on demo tapes to Nashville and Los Angeles. Not finding success with pop music, she began writing more contemporary gospel music.<ref name=\":4\" /> Her first church song was written in 1976, entitled \"''I'll Follow Jesus''.\"<ref name=\":7\" /> She sent the sheet music to local bookstores and partnered with LDS musician [[Merrill Jenson]] to produce more music.<ref name=\":4\" /> Perry released her first album ''Where is Heaven'' in 1978. Two years later, she created a traveling musical called \"''It's a Miracle''\" which was performed in 239 different locations.<ref name=\":2\" /> She and her husband founded Prime Recordings, a music production business.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\nPerry started her career writing her own melodies and words. Later on, she also wrote music to accompany words written by others. She created melodies to the works of [[Emily H. Woodmansee]], [[Gordon B. Hinckley]], and many others.<ref name=\":2\" /> She has also collaborated with [[Orrin Hatch]] to create six albums of songs.<ref name=\":5\">{{Cite web|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171207152826/http://musichousepublications.com:80/our-composers/janice-kapp-perry/|title=Janice Kapp Perry {{!}} Music House Publications|date=2017-12-07|access-date=2018-11-01}}</ref> In 2001, their song \"''Heal our Land''\" was performed at the [[National Prayer Breakfast]] and again in 2005 for the presidential inauguration of [[George W. Bush]].<ref name=\":1\" /> In early 2008, Perry set LDS Church president Gordon B. Hinckley's poem, \"''What is this Thing Called Death''\", to music after one of her nieces died. It was sung by the [[Mormon Tabernacle Choir]] at Hinckley's funeral.<ref>[http://deseretnews.com/article/1,5143,695249715,00.html \"Leader's poetry to become hymn\"], ''[[Deseret Morning News]]'', February 3, 2008.</ref>\n\nPerry was a prolific composer. She wrote over 1,200 songs, which she compiled into more than 75 albums. She also has written eight [[cantata]]s,<ref name=\":7\" /> two of which have been performed in the [[Salt Lake Tabernacle]],<ref name=\":8\" /> and a number of musicals.<ref name=\":6\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.janicekappperry.com/index.php?action=catalog&node=foreignlang&phpsessid=flkfnjjqfga1d8d7m2jl198at0|title=Janice Kapp Perry|website=www.janicekappperry.com|access-date=2018-11-01}}</ref> She is a member of the Utah Composers Guild, and has traveled all over the world to perform her work, including to Japan and Taiwan.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.deseretnews.com/article/705368396/The-songs-keep-coming-for-Janice-Kapp-Perry.html|title=The songs keep coming for Janice Kapp Perry|last=Wadley|first=Carma|date=2011-03-10|work=DeseretNews.com|access-date=2018-11-15|language=en}}</ref>\n\n===A Child's Prayer===\nDuring Perry's career, a mysterious pain left one of her hands paralyzed. As doctors were not able to find a solution, it became especially difficult to play the piano and compose music. Despite this, she continued to write songs, learning to compose them in her head instead.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://universe.byu.edu/2014/06/07/janice-kapp-perry-simple-contributions-through-trials/|title=Janice Kapp Perry: Simple contributions through trials - The Daily Universe|date=2014-06-07|work=The Daily Universe|access-date=2018-11-01|language=en-US}}</ref> In a moment of particular despair over her hand, Perry wrote a song entitled \"''Lord Are You There?''\" which she later reworked and simplified to become her beloved \"''A Child's Prayer''.\" There was some controversy with the song, as the church's [[Priesthood Correlation Program|correlation committee]] believed the lyrics should include formal prayer language, such as \"Thee\" and \"Thou\", but Perry argued that a child would not use those words when praying. The song ultimately remained the same.<ref name=\":8\">{{Cite book|title=We Shall Make Music: Stories of the Primary Songs and How They Came to Be|last=Graham|first=Patricia Kelsey|publisher=Cedar Fort|year=2007|isbn=0882908189|location=|pages=49\u201350,107}}</ref>\n\n==Performances==\nHer work has been performed by many people and in many places. This includes [[Brooks & Dunn]], the Mormon Tabernacle Choir, and [[Gladys Knight]]. Her music has also appeared on television programs like [[Robert Schuller]]'s program ''[[Hour of Power]]'' and [[The Oprah Winfrey Show]] on their episode following [[September 11 attacks|the attacks on 9/11.]]<ref name=\":5\" /> Pianist [[Marvin Goldstein]] also produced albums where he covers Perry's songs.<ref>{{Citation|title=Janice Kapp Perry Favorites Featuring Pianist Marvin Goldstein Vol 1 by Janice Kapp Perry & Marvin Goldstein|date=1991-01-01|url=https://itunes.apple.com/us/album/janice-kapp-perry-favorites-featuring-pianist-marvin/313771551|language=en-US|access-date=2018-11-07}}</ref>\n\n== Personal life ==\n[[File:JKP at EiZ.jpg|thumb|Janice Kapp Perry, center, in 2019]]\nPerry met her husband, Doug, in a music class while they both attended BYU. On September 26, 1958 just before she turned 20, they were married in the [[Logan Utah Temple]]. They had five children together<ref name=\":0\" /> and fostered many other children.<ref name=\":4\" />\n\nWhile raising her family, Perry joined and created community softball leagues, leading them to win many tournaments. She also enjoyed volleyball, racquetball and basketball. She sang in church and local community choirs and was selected to sing with the Mormon Tabernacle Choir. She sang first alto as a member of the choir from 1993 - 1999.<ref name=\":3\" /> Soon after, she and her husband served as LDS Church [[Missionary (LDS Church)|missionaries]] in Chile. When they left their mission, the couple had organized four choirs composed of local church members and young missionaries also assigned there.<ref name=\":3\" />\n\nShe currently resides in [[Provo, Utah]].<ref name=\":2\" />\n\n== Awards and documentaries==\nIn 1994, Perry was honored with the Exemplary Woman Award from Ricks College (now [[Brigham Young University\u2013Idaho|BYU-Idaho]]).<ref name=\":5\" /> In 1997, she was awarded the BYU Alumni Distinguished Service Award.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://homecoming.byu.edu/university-awards/past|title=homecoming.byu.edu|website=homecoming.byu.edu|access-date=2018-11-07}}</ref> In 1998, she was awarded the National George Washington Medal of Honor from the Freedoms Foundation at Valley Forge for the album she wrote with Orrin Hatch. In 1999, Perry won two awards: the Exceptional Merit Award from the LDS Booksellers Association, and the Heritage Award from the Utah/California Women. In 2001, the Faith Centered Music Association honored Perry with their Lifetime Achievement Award.<ref name=\":5\" />\n\nIn LDS Living's \"100 Greatest LDS Songs of All Time\" Perry's \"''A Child's Prayer''\" topped the list at #1. Other songs of hers made the list as well. \"''We'll Bring the World His Truth''\" stood at #8, \"''No Ordinary Man''\" at #13, \"''Love is Spoken Here''\" at #19, \"''In the Hollow of Thy Hand''\" at #21, \"''I Love to See the Temple''\" at #22, \"''His Image in Your Countenance''\" at #24, and \"''I Walk By Faith''\" at #27.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.ldsliving.com/LDS-Living-Presents-the-Top-100-Greatest-LDS-Songs-of-All-Time/s/71356|title=LDS Living Presents the Top 100 Greatest LDS Songs of All Time|date=2012-12-26|work=LDS Living|access-date=2018-11-15}}</ref>\n\nIn 2000, Perry wrote a book about the stories behind her songs entitled \"Songs From My Heart.\"<ref>{{Cite book|title=Songs From My Heart|last=Perry|first=Janice Kapp|publisher=Sounds of Zion|year=2000|isbn=1886472653|location=|pages=}}</ref> There was also a documentary made about her called \"''Janice Kapp Perry: A Life of Service and Song''\" which premiered in 2009.<ref>{{Citation|title=Janice Kapp Perry: A Life of Service and Song|url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt2621902/|access-date=2018-11-15}}</ref>\n\n== Selected discography<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://itunes.apple.com/us/artist/janice-kapp-perry/118798761#see-all/full-albums|title=Janice Kapp Perry on Apple Music|website=Apple Music|language=en-US|access-date=2018-11-08}}</ref> ==\n\n* ''Where is Heaven'' (1978)\n* ''In the Hollow of Thy Hand'' (1980)\n* ''We'll Bring the World His Truth'' (1982)\n* ''The Things of Eternity'' (1982)\n* ''I'm Trying to Be Like Jesus'' (1982)\n* ''With All My Heart'' (1983)\n* ''A Time to Share'' (1986)\n* ''Su Luz en Mi'' (1986)\n* ''There Will Be Light'' (1988)\n* ''The Church of Jesus Christ'' (1989)\n* ''Scripture Scouts: Musical Adventures in the New Testament'' (1992)\n* ''Scripture Scouts: Musical Adventures with the Articles of Faith'' (1992)\n* ''A Song of the Heart'' (1998)\n* ''When a Prophet Speaks'' (2000)\n* ''Janice Kapp Perry's Celtic Variations'' (2002)\n* ''Los Cl\u00e1sicos de Janice Kapp Perry Vol. 1, 2'' (2004)\n* ''Canta Mi Coraz\u00f3n'' (2004)\n* ''A Woman's Heart'' (2009)\n* ''Let's Sing About Latter-Day Prophets'' (2009)\n* ''Por Meios Pequenos e Simples'' (2009)\n* ''When Love Leads the Way: 11 Songs in Japanese'' (2009)\n* ''Sua Luz Em Mim'' (2009)\n* ''Let Me Be A Light: 11 Songs in Japanese'' (2009)\n* ''In the Arms of His Love'' (2009)\n* ''A Gift of Love'' (2009)\n* ''Soft Sounds for a Soothing Sunday, Vol. 1,2,3,& 4'' (2010)\n* ''He Brought Me Light'' (2010)\n* ''The Book of Mormon Has Come Forth'' (2011)\n* ''Soft Sounds for a Soothing Sunday, Vol. V, VI'' (2011)\n* ''Beloved Double Melodies of Janice Kapp Perry'' (2011)\n* ''As A Child of God'' (2012)\n* ''Soft Sounds for a Soothing Sunday, Vol. VII, VIII'' (2012)\n* ''Soft Sounds for a Soothing Sunday, Vol. IX, X'' (2013)\n* ''Merry Christmas to You'' (2013)\n* ''Christmas Magic All Around'' (2013)\n* ''My Faith in Jesus Leads Me On'' (2013)\n* ''Soft Sounds for a Soothing Sunday, Vol XII, XIII'' (2014)\n* ''Book of Mormon Heroes'' (2017)\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Perry, Janice Kapp}}\n[[Category:1938 births]]\n[[Category:21st-century Mormon missionaries]]\n[[Category:American Latter Day Saint hymnwriters]]\n[[Category:American Mormon missionaries in Chile]]\n[[Category:Brigham Young University alumni]]\n[[Category:Female Mormon missionaries]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Mormon Tabernacle Choir members]]\n[[Category:Musicians from Ogden, Utah]]\n[[Category:Musicians from Provo, Utah]]\n[[Category:American female singer-songwriters]]\n[[Category:American singer-songwriters]]\n[[Category:Women religious writers]]\n[[Category:American female songwriters]]\n[[Category:American songwriters]]\n[[Category:Children's songwriters]]\n[[Category:Women hymnwriters]]\n[[Category:American women non-fiction writers]]\n[[Category:People from Vale, Oregon]]\n", "text_old": "{{For2|the performance artist|[[Janice Perry]]|the Los Angeles politician|[[Jan Perry]]}}\n\n[[File:JKP head crop.jpg|thumb|Janice Kapp Perry in 2019]]\n'''Janice Kapp Perry''' (born 1938) is a composer, songwriter, and author. She is most notable for her work related to her membership in [[The Church of Jesus Christ of Latter-day Saints]] (LDS Church). She has written over 1,200 songs, which appear in the church's [[Hymns of The Church of Jesus Christ of Latter-day Saints (1985 book)|official hymnal]], ''[[Children's Songbook]]'', and many personal albums, songbooks, and musicals. Perry has also composed albums in Spanish, Portuguese, Chinese, Japanese, and Korean.\n\n== Early life ==\nPerry was born on October 1, 1938 in [[Ogden, Utah]], and spent her childhood on a farm in [[Vale, Oregon]]. She grew up in a very musical family. Her mother, Ruth, played the piano and wrote musicals for the children to perform in the community. Her father, Jacob, learned to play the drums to accompany his wife in a family band.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://ldsmag.com/happy-birthday-to-janice-kapp-perry-looking-back-on-80-years/|title=Happy Birthday to Janice Kapp Perry: Looking Back on 80 Years!|website=LDS Magazine|access-date=2018-11-01}}</ref> After her father died, Perry played the drums in his place.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite news|url=https://magazine.byu.edu/article/a-testimony-through-song/|title=Janice Kapp Perry wrote over 160 hymns as a way to share her testimony|work=BYU Magazine|access-date=2018-11-01|language=en-US}}</ref> The children in the family also performed in a quartet.<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.deseretnews.com/article/900035128/mormon-songwriter-janice-kapp-perry-talks-new-hymn-book.html|title=Beloved church songwriter Janice Kapp Perry weighs in on the new hymn book|last=Robinson|first=Doug|date=2018-10-05|work=DeseretNews.com|access-date=2018-11-01|language=en}}</ref> In high school, she was in the band, playing snare drum and tympani.<ref name=\":7\">{{Cite book|title=Women of Character: Profiles of 100 Prominent LDS Women|last=Black|first=Susan Easton|last2=Woodger|first2=Mary Jane|publisher=Covenant Communications Inc.|year=2011|isbn=9781680470185|location=American Fork, Utah|pages=227\u2013229}}</ref> She also wrote her very first song, titled ''\"I Walked in God's Garden.\"''<ref name=\":1\" /> Though music was an important part of her childhood, Perry spent most of her time playing sports. She loved volleyball, basketball and even football.<ref name=\":7\" /> She especially loved softball.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\nPerry attended [[Brigham Young University]] (BYU) where she studied music composition and theory. While there, she played in BYU's concert band, orchestra<ref name=\":2\" /> and sang in the choir.<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite web|url=https://ldsmag.com/article-1-11618/|title=Thoughts from a Lifelong Choir Junkie|website=LDS Magazine|access-date=2018-11-01}}</ref>\n\n== Compositions ==\nAt the age of 38, Perry broke one of her ankles during one of her basketball games. Her television broke at the same time. With the extra time the incidents afforded her, she was assigned by her ward to compose music for their ward road show.<ref name=\":1\" /> She entered church song writing competitions and wrote new songs for her local church community.<ref name=\":4\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.deseretnews.com/article/600113781/Utahns-noted-for-great-notes.html|title=Utahn's noted for great notes|last=Robinson|first=Doug|date=2005-02-22|work=DeseretNews.com|access-date=2018-11-01|language=en}}</ref>\n\nPerry experimented with many styles at the beginning of her career, writing pop music that she sent on demo tapes to Nashville and Los Angeles. Not finding success with pop music, she began writing more contemporary gospel music.<ref name=\":4\" /> Her first church song was written in 1976, entitled \"''I'll Follow Jesus''.\"<ref name=\":7\" /> She sent the sheet music to local bookstores and partnered with LDS musician [[Merrill Jenson]] to produce more music.<ref name=\":4\" /> Perry released her first album ''Where is Heaven'' in 1978. Two years later, she created a traveling musical called \"''It's a Miracle''\" which was performed in 239 different locations.<ref name=\":2\" /> She and her husband founded Prime Recordings, a music production business.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\nPerry started her career writing her own melodies and words. Later on, she also wrote music to accompany words written by others. She created melodies to the works of [[Emily H. Woodmansee]], [[Gordon B. Hinckley]], and many others.<ref name=\":2\" /> She has also collaborated with [[Orrin Hatch]] to create six albums of songs.<ref name=\":5\">{{Cite web|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171207152826/http://musichousepublications.com:80/our-composers/janice-kapp-perry/|title=Janice Kapp Perry {{!}} Music House Publications|date=2017-12-07|access-date=2018-11-01}}</ref> In 2001, their song \"''Heal our Land''\" was performed at the [[National Prayer Breakfast]] and again in 2005 for the presidential inauguration of [[George W. Bush]].<ref name=\":1\" /> In early 2008, Perry set LDS Church president Gordon B. Hinckley's poem, \"''What is this Thing Called Death''\", to music after one of her nieces died. It was sung by the [[Mormon Tabernacle Choir]] at Hinckley's funeral.<ref>[http://deseretnews.com/article/1,5143,695249715,00.html \"Leader's poetry to become hymn\"], ''[[Deseret Morning News]]'', February 3, 2008.</ref>\n\nPerry was a prolific composer. She wrote over 1,200 songs, which she compiled into more than 75 albums. She also has written eight [[cantata]]s,<ref name=\":7\" /> two of which have been performed in the [[Salt Lake Tabernacle]],<ref name=\":8\" /> and a number of musicals.<ref name=\":6\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.janicekappperry.com/index.php?action=catalog&node=foreignlang&phpsessid=flkfnjjqfga1d8d7m2jl198at0|title=Janice Kapp Perry|website=www.janicekappperry.com|access-date=2018-11-01}}</ref> She is a member of the Utah Composers Guild, and has traveled all over the world to perform her work, including to Japan and Taiwan.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.deseretnews.com/article/705368396/The-songs-keep-coming-for-Janice-Kapp-Perry.html|title=The songs keep coming for Janice Kapp Perry|last=Wadley|first=Carma|date=2011-03-10|work=DeseretNews.com|access-date=2018-11-15|language=en}}</ref>\n\n===A Child's Prayer===\nDuring Perry's career, a mysterious pain left one of her hands paralyzed. As doctors were not able to find a solution, it became especially difficult to play the piano and compose music. Despite this, she continued to write songs, learning to compose them in her head instead.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://universe.byu.edu/2014/06/07/janice-kapp-perry-simple-contributions-through-trials/|title=Janice Kapp Perry: Simple contributions through trials - The Daily Universe|date=2014-06-07|work=The Daily Universe|access-date=2018-11-01|language=en-US}}</ref> In a moment of particular despair over her hand, Perry wrote a song entitled \"''Lord Are You There?''\" which she later reworked and simplified to become her beloved \"''A Child's Prayer''.\" There was some controversy with the song, as the church's [[Priesthood Correlation Program|correlation committee]] believed the lyrics should include formal prayer language, such as \"Thee\" and \"Thou\", but Perry argued that a child would not use those words when praying. The song ultimately remained the same.<ref name=\":8\">{{Cite book|title=We Shall Make Music: Stories of the Primary Songs and How They Came to Be|last=Graham|first=Patricia Kelsey|publisher=Cedar Fort|year=2007|isbn=0882908189|location=|pages=49\u201350,107}}</ref>\n\n==Performances==\nHer work has been performed by many people and in many places. This includes [[Brooks & Dunn]], the Mormon Tabernacle Choir, and [[Gladys Knight]]. Her music has also appeared on television programs like [[Robert Schuller]]'s program ''[[Hour of Power]]'' and [[The Oprah Winfrey Show]] on their episode following [[September 11 attacks|the attacks on 9/11.]]<ref name=\":5\" /> Pianist [[Marvin Goldstein]] also produced albums where he covers Perry's songs.<ref>{{Citation|title=Janice Kapp Perry Favorites Featuring Pianist Marvin Goldstein Vol 1 by Janice Kapp Perry & Marvin Goldstein|date=1991-01-01|url=https://itunes.apple.com/us/album/janice-kapp-perry-favorites-featuring-pianist-marvin/313771551|language=en-US|access-date=2018-11-07}}</ref>\n\n== Personal life ==\n[[File:JKP at EiZ.jpg|thumb|Janice Kapp Perry, center, in 2019]]\nPerry met her husband, Doug, in a music class while they both attended BYU. On September 26, 1958 just before she turned 20, they were married in the [[Logan Utah Temple]]. They had five children together<ref name=\":0\" /> and fostered many other children.<ref name=\":4\" />\n\nWhile raising her family, Perry joined and created community softball leagues, leading them to win many tournaments. She also enjoyed volleyball, racquetball and basketball. She sang in church and local community choirs and was selected to sing with the Mormon Tabernacle Choir. She sang first alto as a member of the choir from 1993 - 1999.<ref name=\":3\" /> Soon after, she and her husband served as LDS Church [[Missionary (LDS Church)|missionaries]] in Chile. When they left their mission, the couple had organized four choirs composed of local church members and young missionaries also assigned there.<ref name=\":3\" />\n\nShe currently resides in [[Provo, Utah]].<ref name=\":2\" />\n\n== Awards and documentaries==\nIn 1994, Perry was honored with the Exemplary Woman Award from Ricks College (now [[Brigham Young University\u2013Idaho|BYU-Idaho]]).<ref name=\":5\" /> In 1997, she was awarded the BYU Alumni Distinguished Service Award.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://homecoming.byu.edu/university-awards/past|title=homecoming.byu.edu|website=homecoming.byu.edu|access-date=2018-11-07}}</ref> In 1998, she was awarded the National George Washington Medal of Honor from the Freedoms Foundation at Valley Forge for the album she wrote with Orrin Hatch. In 1999, Perry won two awards: the Exceptional Merit Award from the LDS Booksellers Association, and the Heritage Award from the Utah/California Women. In 2001, the Faith Centered Music Association honored Perry with their Lifetime Achievement Award.<ref name=\":5\" />\n\nIn LDS Living's \"100 Greatest LDS Songs of All Time\" Perry's \"''A Child's Prayer''\" topped the list at #1. Other songs of hers made the list as well. \"''We'll Bring the World His Truth''\" stood at #8, \"''No Ordinary Man''\" at #13, \"''Love is Spoken Here''\" at #19, \"''In the Hollow of Thy Hand''\" at #21, \"''I Love to See the Temple''\" at #22, \"''His Image in Your Countenance''\" at #24, and \"''I Walk By Faith''\" at #27.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.ldsliving.com/LDS-Living-Presents-the-Top-100-Greatest-LDS-Songs-of-All-Time/s/71356|title=LDS Living Presents the Top 100 Greatest LDS Songs of All Time|date=2012-12-26|work=LDS Living|access-date=2018-11-15}}</ref>\n\nIn 2000, Perry wrote a book about the stories behind her songs entitled \"Songs From My Heart.\"<ref>{{Cite book|title=Songs From My Heart|last=Perry|first=Janice Kapp|publisher=Sounds of Zion|year=2000|isbn=1886472653|location=|pages=}}</ref> There was also a documentary made about her called \"''Janice Kapp Perry: A Life of Service and Song''\" which premiered in 2009.<ref>{{Citation|title=Janice Kapp Perry: A Life of Service and Song|url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt2621902/|access-date=2018-11-15}}</ref>\n\n== Selected discography<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://itunes.apple.com/us/artist/janice-kapp-perry/118798761#see-all/full-albums|title=Janice Kapp Perry on Apple Music|website=Apple Music|language=en-US|access-date=2018-11-08}}</ref> ==\n\n* ''Where is Heaven'' (1978)\n* ''In the Hollow of Thy Hand'' (1980)\n* ''We'll Bring the World His Truth'' (1982)\n* ''The Things of Eternity'' (1982)\n* ''I'm Trying to Be Like Jesus'' (1982)\n* ''With All My Heart'' (1983)\n* ''A Time to Share'' (1986)\n* ''Su Luz en Mi'' (1986)\n* ''There Will Be Light'' (1988)\n* ''The Church of Jesus Christ'' (1989)\n* ''Scripture Scouts: Musical Adventures in the New Testament'' (1992)\n* ''Scripture Scouts: Musical Adventures with the Articles of Faith'' (1992)\n* ''A Song of the Heart'' (1998)\n* ''When a Prophet Speaks'' (2000)\n* ''Janice Kapp Perry's Celtic Variations'' (2002)\n* ''Los Cl\u00e1sicos de Janice Kapp Perry Vol. 1, 2'' (2004)\n* ''Canta Mi Coraz\u00f3n'' (2004)\n* ''A Woman's Heart'' (2009)\n* ''Let's Sing About Latter-Day Prophets'' (2009)\n* ''Por Meios Pequenos e Simples'' (2009)\n* ''When Love Leads the Way: 11 Songs in Japanese'' (2009)\n* ''Sua Luz Em Mim'' (2009)\n* ''Let Me Be A Light: 11 Songs in Japanese'' (2009)\n* ''In the Arms of His Love'' (2009)\n* ''A Gift of Love'' (2009)\n* ''Soft Sounds for a Soothing Sunday, Vol. 1,2,3,& 4'' (2010)\n* ''He Brought Me Light'' (2010)\n* ''The Book of Mormon Has Come Forth'' (2011)\n* ''Soft Sounds for a Soothing Sunday, Vol. V, VI'' (2011)\n* ''Beloved Double Melodies of Janice Kapp Perry'' (2011)\n* ''As A Child of God'' (2012)\n* ''Soft Sounds for a Soothing Sunday, Vol. VII, VIII'' (2012)\n* ''Soft Sounds for a Soothing Sunday, Vol. IX, X'' (2013)\n* ''Merry Christmas to You'' (2013)\n* ''Christmas Magic All Around'' (2013)\n* ''My Faith in Jesus Leads Me On'' (2013)\n* ''Soft Sounds for a Soothing Sunday, Vol XII, XIII'' (2014)\n* ''Book of Mormon Heroes'' (2017)\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Perry, Janice Kapp}}\n[[Category:1938 births]]\n[[Category:21st-century Mormon missionaries]]\n[[Category:American Latter Day Saint hymnwriters]]\n[[Category:American Mormon missionaries in Chile]]\n[[Category:Brigham Young University alumni]]\n[[Category:Female Mormon missionaries]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Mormon Tabernacle Choir members]]\n[[Category:Musicians from Ogden, Utah]]\n[[Category:Musicians from Provo, Utah]]\n[[Category:American female singer-songwriters]]\n[[Category:American singer-songwriters]]\n[[Category:Women religious writers]]\n[[Category:American female songwriters]]\n[[Category:American songwriters]]\n[[Category:Children's songwriters]]\n[[Category:Women hymnwriters]]\n[[Category:American women non-fiction writers]]\n[[Category:People from Vale, Oregon]]\n", "name_user": "Nihiltres", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200etop:Simplified hatnote syntax", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Janice_Kapp_Perry"}
